<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Tall Ships Come To NYC  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dutch tall ship Eendracht slipped into New
York harbor on Thursday, a prelude to a Fourth of July spectacle
billed as the largest maritime event in peacetime.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 wind-powered tall ships from at least 50 nations plus
40 modern warships from 23 navies are expected for a weeklong
spectacle, with most of the ships filing into the harbor on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The beauty of a ship is when she's driven by the wind,'' said
retired Admiral Paul Welling, a 35-year U.S. Coast Guard veteran
and chief operating officer of OpSail 2000.
</P>
<P>
   During the Fourth of July festivities Monday, President Clinton
is expected to review a fleet comprising almost 10,000 military
personnel, and the celebration, expected to draw more than 4
million spectators, is to be capped with fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of other craft are also expected to flood New
York waters to watch, nearly three times the number at the 1986
Statue of Liberty centennial, according to the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the main port of call in the tall ships' nine-week
coastal cruise. The summer tour, the fifth since Opsail began,
started May 19 in San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The parade left Baltimore early Thursday, led by the 170-foot
long Pride of Baltimore II, with cannons firing. After leaving New
York, its ships are to stop in New London, Conn., and Portland,
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Sail was established by President John F. Kennedy in
1961 to promote cultural exchanges. The first Opsail celebrated New
York City's World's Fair in 1964; others coincided with milestones
such as the 1976 U.S. bicentennial and the 500th anniversary in
1992 of Christopher Columbus' arrival in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Operation Sail: http://www.opsail2000.org
</P>
<P>
   New London: http://www.opsail2000ct.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
