<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DEC unveils management plan for Adirondack landmark  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The rustic buildings at a nationally
recognized Adirondack Park camp will be preserved and the natural
character of the land retained under a management plan released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The management plan drafted by the state Department of
Environmental Conservation proposes turning 32 acres around Camp
Santanoni into an ''Historic Area,'' creating a tourist attraction
while protecting the wild forest that surrounds the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1892 by banker Robert C. Pruyn, the great camp - one of
the most notable in the region - has hosted such dignitaries as
Gov. Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   One of three properties in the 6-million-acre Adirondack Park
listed on the National Register of Historic Places, Camp Santanoni
is included in the 70,000-acre Vanderwhacker Wild Forest Area in
Newcomb, Essex County, 93 miles north of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   It also is listed on the state Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed historic area includes preservation of three
complexes of buildings: The gatehouse, the farm and the great camp.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings are all connected by a 5-mile carriage road that
would be off-limits to motor vehicles, snowmobiles and horses. The
plan would allow some motorized access for maintenance and
emergency vehicles and for the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   The only substantive change in the land will be the provision of
extra parking at the gatehouse complex.
</P>
<P>
   All of the buildings will be preserved, a change from the
initial plan that recommended removing the farm manager's cottage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Camp Santanoni is a natural, cultural and historical treasure
that exemplifies the very best of the Adirondack Great Camps and
provides the public with an opportunity to experience and learn
about an important aspect of Adirondack and New York State
heritage,'' said DEC Commissioner John P. Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   The new draft, altered since it was first proposed in October,
also reduces the number of acres changed from wild forest to
historic, from 75 to 32. The acreage was reduced by narrowing a
corridor of land along the road from 100 to 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Another change from October's draft is the omission of a plan to
restore a 2 1-2 acre orchard and garden area, leaving the land as
part of the Vanderwhacker forest area. That sits well with The
Adirondack Mountain Club, according to counsel Neil Woodworth.
</P>
<P>
   The club has supported the management plan for Camp Santanoni
but thought the restoration of orchard and farm land may have been
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a preservation standpoint, are these changes in the right
direction? Sure,'' Woodworth said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan now goes to the Adirondack Park Agency to determine if
it complies with the Adirondack State Land Master Plan, a 1971
document that guides land use in the park. The APA's State Land
Committee will discuss the plan July 13 and forward a
recommendation to the full APA for a vote on July 14.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, reclassification of the land falls to Gov. George E.
Pataki.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
