<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seneca Nation president urges Pataki to veto Internet cigarette bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SALAMANCA, N.Y. (AP) - Fearing their sovereignty is in peril,
the Seneca Nation of Indians is urging Gov. George Pataki to veto a
bill they claim would affect all tribal business, not just their
lucrative Internet cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fear that this bill will be used to stop commerce on our
reservations. We fear that this bill, if signed by the governor,
would be used by others to erode our inherent sovereignty,'' Seneca
Nation of Indians president Duane James Ray said at a press
conference Thursday. ''The broad way that the law is written, it
could affect all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Both houses of the legislature passed the measure and it awaits
only a a signature from the governor - currently traveling in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law would penalize carriers such as United Parcel
Service and Federal Express for delivering cigarettes that do not
meet state tax regulations by carrying the state tax stamp. That
would cover all cigarettes sold from Seneca reservations, where
Indians are allowed to sell tax-free cigarettes at much lower
prices than off-reservation outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when word of the bill's approval came to light, some
Seneca Indians threatened to hold tire-fire protests along the New
York State Thruway.
</P>
<P>
   Ray hoped it wouldn't come to that.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want the snowball effect to happen,'' he said. ''The
Seneca Nation doesn't want this to happen but we also have rights
that we have to protect. And at this point in time, it looks like
(the bill) is infringing on our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the nation was especially disappointed the bill passed
unanimously without review or study.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the bill goes against a 148-year-old treaty in which
the state recognized the Seneca Nation's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our businesses, and the businesses operated by our members,
are essential to our well-being and our economy,'' he said.
''Indian people in this state suffer from the highest rates of
poverty and unemployment. Jobs and economic opportunities are few
and far between. Retail enterprises are a small measure to fill
these unmet needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his departure overseas, Pataki called it a ''fair bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not aimed at going after sales on Indian Nations that
have existed. But we do have to make sure that those who want to
bootleg cigarettes illegally and have bootlegged cigarettes
illegally face tougher penalties and tougher laws,'' Pataki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 0015 </TRAILER>
