<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson Plans Vigil at Hanging Site  </HEADLINE>
By RON HARRIST
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson says he has been
assured by federal and state authorities that sufficient manpower
is being used to investigate the hanging death of a black
Mississippi teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Raynard Johnson, 17, was found hanging from a pecan tree a few
yards from the front door of his rural Marion County home June 16.
Officials said autopsy findings were consistent with suicide, but
Johnson's family questioned the ruling and called on Jackson and
others to demand a federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also said Thursday he believes there are suspects in the
case, although officials have refused to confirm or deny that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though the government has not officially declared someone
to be on the suspect list, there are persons who are aware of the
climate before the lynching,'' Jackson told The Associated Press.
He said many things point to a racially motivated killing,
including the fact that Johnson and his brother had been friends
with two 17-year-old white girls.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is conducting a preliminary probe, and state authorities
say their investigations continue to be a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's Chicago office said a second autopsy by a forensic
pathologist at the family's request also found injuries consistent
with suicide, however toxicology tests were incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who spoke at the teen's funeral on Tuesday, said he
plans to lead a prayer vigil Sunday at the site of the hanging to
focus national attention on the death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
