<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labastida Still Contender in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By KEN GUGGENHEIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Opinion polls may show a statistical tie in
Mexico's presidential race and the opposition may have its best
shot of ending the governing party's 71 years in power. But don't
call Sunday's election a toss-up.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, is still the man to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Poll numbers alone give Labastida an edge over top rival Vicente
Fox of the center-right National Action Party. That advantage is
magnified by Labastida's mightiest weapon: the PRI's powerful
electoral machine -- local politicians, unions and peasant groups
that through persuasion, fear and favors, deliver the PRI vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, meanwhile, has failed to capture the full opposition vote.
Third-place candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas retains a solid core of
support. Pollsters say Cardenas can't win, but he can capture
enough of the anti-PRI vote to hurt Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a Fox victory cannot be ruled out. A small-state governor
from a party with limited regional support, Fox has staged a
remarkable three-year campaign, emerging as the biggest threat ever
to the PRI's power.
</P>
<P>
   He's proven wrong the many skeptics who expected his candidacy
to fade. But he still has a way to go to capture the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls in the last week of the campaign have shown
Labastida leading Fox by 3 or 4 percentage points. Given the margin
of error of the polls -- typically 2.5 percentage points -- a Fox
victory is considered possible, so the race is described as a
statistical tie. Yet the advantage remains with Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Some opinion polls may actually overstate Fox's support.
Labastida has tremendous strength in remote, rural areas difficult
to reach by pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   And the polls don't factor in the PRI's superiority in getting
out the vote. Labastida showed how effective the PRI's machine can
be, riding it to a landslide victory in the party's first
presidential primary in November.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's party and his parallel ''Friends of Fox'' organization
don't have anything comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Labastida's support is a diehard PRI vote that Fox has
no chance of capturing. For many Mexicans, a vote for the PRI is
almost instinctive, a sign of national pride. Others fear the loss
of social programs. And some votes are bought by gifts provided by
local PRI governments, such as bicycles and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's best hope has been to lure Cardenas' backers, persuading
them that Fox is the only candidate who can stop the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cardenas' support has not waned. In opinion polls, he hovers
around 15 percent to 18 percent. He insists he will win and, in the
final weeks of the campaign, has stepped up attacks on Fox, whom he
accuses of selling out to U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   Fox still has a few strengths. He has the support of younger,
better-educated, urban voters. A giant turnout in major cities
would be a big boost. Also, opinion polls show many voters were
still undecided in the final weeks of the campaign -- and some
analysts say many of them may be Fox supporters scared to state
their preference.
</P>
<P>
   Fox stands to benefit from years of electoral reforms that have
led to opposition victories in state and local elections, cost the
PRI its majority in Congress and have made this presidential
campaign the fairest in modern Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters have a feverish enthusiasm that's rare in Mexican
politics. They can taste what would be an astonishing victory that,
to them, represents not only the triumph of a candidate but a giant
leap in Mexican democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Fox can only hope that on Sunday, that fever will be contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Ken Guggenheim, a former Mexico City
correspondent for The Associated Press, now covers Latin American
issues for the AP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
