<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Claims He Has Hostages at Disney  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE SCHNEIDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- An armed man held his 4-year-old
son and a waiter hostage Thursday at a Walt Disney World hotel and
demanded to speak to his estranged wife, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators and a police psychologist talked to the man and the
hostage at the Boardwalk Inn, said Sgt. Bernie Presha, a spokesman
for the sheriff's office. The waiter was taken hostage when he
delivered food to the man's hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has threatened to harm himself and he has threatened to
harm the people with him,'' said Jim Solomons, another sheriff's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The man, identified by officials as 39-year-old Bismark
Rodriguez, called television station WKMG twice and said he hadn't
seen his other three children in 30 days and he wanted to speak
with them and his wife. He said he and his wife of 14 years are
going through a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I wanted was a divorce. ... She said we couldn't be
friends if we had a divorce,'' he told the station. ''Twenty times
she's taken my kids, then she goes to court, plays her little
things and I'm too nervous to tell them how I feel. All they do is
'OK, whatever, whatever' and the woman's always right and that's
not true.''
</P>
<P>
   He claimed to have several guns and a bomb and said he would
release the hostages of he could speak to his wife. The hostages,
identified as Rodriguez's son Christopher and 42-year-old Rafael
Carmona, were still being held after midnight, about 10 hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   Some rooms in the 910-room deluxe hotel, which has an Atlantic
City boardwalk theme, were evacuated. The rest of the sprawling
resort, which includes 17 hotels operated by Disney, was operating
normally, Presha said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez called the Orlando FBI office and requested a hostage
negotiator, Orange County Sheriff Kevin Beary said. Rodriguez
recently lived in nearby Kissimmee
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just trying to keep him calmed down,'' Beary said,
adding that Rodriguez's relatives were on their way to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Powell, a visitor from LeSueur, Minn., was headed to a
restaurant near the hotel when she saw the sheriff's helicopters
and dozens of officers blocking off the area, in the heart of the
Walt Disney World complex.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't expect this to happen here,'' Powell said. ''You
think you're in a fantasy land here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
