<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Claims He Has Hostages at Disney
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- A armed man held his 4-year-old son and a
waiter hostage Thursday at a Walt Disney World hotel and demanded to speak to
his estranged wife, authorities said. Negotiators and a police psychologist
talked to the man and the hostage at the Boardwalk Inn, said Sgt. Bernie Presha,
a spokesman for the sheriff's office. The waiter was taken hostage when he
delivered food to the man's hotel room. The man, identified by officials as
39-year-old Bismark Rodriguez, called television station WKMG twice and said he
hadn't seen his other three children in 30 days and he wanted to speak with them
and his wife. He said he and his wife of 14 years are going through a divorce.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate OKs Limited Patient Rights
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-controlled Senate voted Thursday night for
limited new patient protections, including a restricted right to sue HMOs,
overriding Democratic protests that the plan was an election-year sham. The vote
was 51-47, largely along party lines, and capped two weeks of intense
partisanship in both the House and Senate over health care issues expected to
resonate in the fall campaign. Senate GOP Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., said the
proposal marked a ''significant concession'' over legislation that Republicans
approved last year that barred lawsuits.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Gore Assures Women on Abortion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A day after the Supreme Court's narrow vote striking down
a state abortion ban, Tipper Gore said her husband would protect a woman's right
to end a pregnancy and urged women supporters to help elect him president in
November. On Wednesday, Vice President and Democratic presidential contender Al
Gore said the next president will fill up to four vacancies on the court and
warned abortion-rights supporters against electing Republican presidential rival
George W. Bush. Bush opposes abortion except in cases of rape, incest or to save
the woman's life.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fire Roars at Wash. Nuke Reservation
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- A wildfire ignited by a car crash raged across the
dry sagebrush of the Hanford nuclear complex Thursday, raising fears that the
flames would spread radioactive material. At least 25 homes were destroyed, and
about 7,000 people were driven from their homes by the second blaze in two
months to threaten a U.S. nuclear weapons installation. The fire, which began
Tuesday, had scorched 190,000 acres.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Illinois Suspends Gas Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Driven by some of the highest gasoline prices in
the nation, Illinois Thursday became the second state to suspend its sales tax
on gas. Legislators, voting in a special session, urged gas stations to pass
along the 5 percent tax savings on the gasoline they sell. If they do, drivers
could see prices fall by 7 or 8 cents a gallon in a state where prices in some
areas have soared well above $2 per gallon. The legislation, which was quickly
signed by Gov. George Ryan, suspends the tax for six months, starting Saturday,
and requires each gas pump to display a sign saying the tax has been lowered and
that prices should reflect the change.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Find Five Dead in Va. Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Police checking on a tip that there might be dead
bodies in a suburban Richmond home said Thursday night they found five bodies in
the residence. Police Chief Carl Baker said a handgun was recovered, but he
would not say whether all the victims were shot. He gave no other details about
what police found inside the home during a short briefing. The tip was called in
to the Chesterfield County Emergency Communications Center, said Don Kappel, the
county's director of public affairs. He said some of the victims knew each
other, but the identities and any relations to one another were being withheld
until relatives could be notified.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Friday as investors were discouraged by
overnight falls in stocks. The Nikkei shed 134.33 points, to 17,341.57 at the
end of the morning session. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
129.75 to close at 10,398.04. The Nasdaq composite index was down 63.11 at
3,877.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rocker, Braves Defeat Mets 6-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- John Rocker pitched a perfect eighth inning Thurday as the
Atlanta Braves beat New York 6-4, ending the Mets' seven-game winning streak.
The crowd of 46,998 jeered as Rocker warmed up, but the booing did not unnerve
him. Rocker struck out Robin Ventura and retired Todd Zeile and Jay Payton on
grounders. Andres Galarraga homered, tripled and drove in four runs as Atlanta
won the opener of a four-game series for the NL East lead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
