<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Embroiled in Discontent  </HEADLINE>
By PRISCILLA CHEUNG
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- First the protesters were radical activists and
students, and there were only a few of them. Then came lawyers and
doctors, teachers and middle-class homeowners, who took to the
streets by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   As Hong Kong prepares this weekend to mark the third anniversary
of its reunification with China, a rash of recent anti-government
protests reflects an unexpected trend in the former British colony:
Citizens are far angrier at their own government than the one in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints involve everything from the territory's
struggling economy and several sweetheart business deals won by
local tycoons to air pollution. Not to mention education, health
care, the civil service and the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest surprise after the handover has been the fact that
Hong Kong people are not able to rule Hong Kong,'' said Sonny Lo, a
political scientist at the University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Britain returned Hong Kong's sovereignty to China on July 1,
1997, after 156 years of colonial rule. Shipping tycoon Tung
Chee-hwa was selected as the territory's leader by a 400-member,
Beijing-appointed committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under Sino-British agreements, Hong Kong can maintain its
capitalist lifestyle for at least 50 years and the local government
can enjoy a high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   But the transition hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   The territory has just begun rebounding from a deep recession
sparked by the Asian financial crisis. Many people remain
unemployed, while others have seen their assets lose value on the
free market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, smog and haze are choking the city like never
before, mainly because of industrial pollution from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ''People gave Tung the benefit of the doubt, but his honeymoon
is over,'' said Timothy Wong, a political analyst at the Institute
of Asia Pacific Studies at Chinese University. ''They are losing
confidence in what was once a highly efficient government after
several blunders.''
</P>
<P>
   When China first sent troops to the territory as Britain
withdrew, many people worried about a possible crackdown on their
personal freedoms, ones that mainland Chinese residents have never
enjoyed under a communist government. That fear led to a series of
protests by radicals and pro-democracy students, but those worries
proved unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most hot-button issues is concern that Hong Kong's
cherished and famous level playing field for businesspeople has
been tilted in favor of well-connected tycoons.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a British-based think tank, the Economist Intelligence
Unit, knocked Hong Kong from No. 1 to sixth place in its ranking of
locations to do business in the next five years. It cited a high
likelihood that the Hong Kong government will give preferential
treatment to local and mainland interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''Much of the deterioration is due to political and regulatory
changes after the 1997 handover to China,'' the Economist
Intelligence Unit said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Li, son of Hong Kong's wealthiest man, Li Ka-shing, won
the right to develop a government lot into a high-tech industrial
park, dubbed the Cyberport, without the routine bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Some powerful property tycoons seemed just as angry as the
protesters in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Li's start-up Internet firm also defeated Singapore
Telecommunications Ltd. in a bid to buy Hong Kong's oldest telecom
firm. Li's bid came amid news reports that Beijing had disapproved
of the Singapore deal because it did not want a foreign firm to
control the local telecom giant.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cronyism in creeping in,'' said Martin Lee, a prominent lawyer
and leader of the opposition Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been controversy over China's handling of the
territory's courts. Lawyers worry that Hong Kong's rule of law --
regarded as a safeguard of human rights and commercial integrity --
is giving way to China's judicial system, where many cases are
tried in closed courts.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, many citizens are angry at massive reforms that
Tung has proposed in education, health care, welfare, tax laws, the
financial markets and the civil service.
</P>
<P>
   Many homeowners, whose apartments have lost half their value,
blame Tung's housing policy. He has introduced measures designed to
keep property prices low and to boost home ownership, and they
depressed the property market, which is vital in this land-strapped
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Tung is too eager to make his mark as the first post-handover
leader and is trying to do too much, too fast, political analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tung doesn't understand that he's running a government, not
his own private business,'' said architect Simon Kao, 45.
</P>
<P>
   ''He always tries to be the big father,'' Kao added. ''You can't
force people to embrace the changes without asking them whether
they wanted anything changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
