<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fliers Aim To Earn Million Miles  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- In the world of frequent flier miles, call
it the Holy Grail.
</P>
<P>
   Latin Pass, a frequent-flier program for a consortium of 10
South and Central American airlines, said it would award 1 million
miles to anyone who took at least one international flight on each
of its member airlines plus a flight on one of its three partner
airlines, stayed three nights in participating hotels and rented a
car for five days from partner agencies.
</P>
<P>
   They gave six months, from Jan. 1 to July 1, to qualify, but Dan
Hacker, a 37-year-old systems analyst from Silver Spring, Md.,
needed just a week.
</P>
<P>
   ''One group figured out a way to do it in three and a half
days,'' Hacker said as he surveyed the plush lobby of polished wood
and marble of the Guatemala City Marriott, a $105-per-night hotel
he spent less than six hours staying in. ''I figured a week was
fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hacker's million-mile quest started June 17 when he left
Baltimore Washington International Airport for Miami on US Airways,
one of the U.S. partner lines. Then it was on to Caracas,
Venezuela, on Aeropostal; to Bogota, Columbia, on Avianca; and to
Quito, Ecuador, on Aces.
</P>
<P>
   From there he flew to Lima, Peru, on Aces (which counted for a
flight on Saeta, a consortium member not operating now), then to
Cuzco on Taca-Peru (a domestic flight that counted because
Taca-Peru doesn't have international flights).
</P>
<P>
   Hacker gave himself a free day to visit the ancient Incan ruins
at Machu Pichu because ''my wife wouldn't let me do this without
actually seeing something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The final phase of the solo journey saw the father of two, who
says he's ''slightly obsessed'' with free mileage, head back to
Lima on Taca, and then take a Copa flight to Panama City; to San
Jose, Costa Rica, and to Guatemala City. Then he flew to San
Salvador, El Salvador, on Aviateca; to Managua, Nicaragua, on Taca;
and to San Jose on Copa, before flying back to Managua on Lacsa.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Miami on Taca, a flight that counted for Nica,
which is not operating now.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been having fun, I really have,'' said Hacker, who
brought three changes of clothes in a single carry-on bag during a
trip that saw him spend only about 27 hours actually in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The whole trip cost him $3,000, but Hacker figures his week of
work is earning him $10,000 -- the estimated value of free tickets
awarded for 1 million frequent flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   Free trips usually cost frequent fliers many more miles than
they actually turn in. For example, a business class trip from the
United States to Europe on any Latin Pass airline costs 90,000
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can fly the whole family to Europe five times for free after
this,'' Hacker said.
</P>
<P>
   He was hardly the first million-mile-trekker whose trip raised
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   ''These people rented a car, but when our concierge asked them
where they were planning to go, they said it was just going to sit
in the parking lot,'' said Melvie Lopez, a desk receptionist at the
Holiday Inn Guatemala -- one of a slew of well-known chains
affiliated with Latin Pass.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Singer, 41, who works for a firm that manages patient
hospital records in Seattle and has exploited all kinds of frequent
flier programs, said Latin Pass is the sweetest deal offered so
far.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every year some idiot in marketing comes up with a program
like this they think three or four people will qualify for,'' said
Singer, whose frequent-flier exploits have taken him everywhere
from La Paz to Laos -- all for free.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Pass reward of 1 million miles, technically enough to
go to the moon and back twice or to circle the globe 43 times, will
also be good on the program's partners -- US Airways, KLM and TWA --
or could be bartered for free nights at hundreds of partner hotels
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Even Latin Pass, where everything from renting a car in Lima to
shopping in certain South Florida-area malls earns you miles,
admits its promotion has worked a bit too well.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people have qualified so far, but would-be
millionaires flying in June won't be tallied for several weeks,
said Guy Booth, the promotion's director.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't create a monster here, but publicity did get a bit
out of control,'' Booth said. ''It has put Latin Pass on the map,
but the costs of all the free miles we will have to give away will
begin to add up.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Latin Pass: http://www.latinpass.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
