<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abortion Ruling Snarls Doctor Vote  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Friday to extend collective
bargaining powers to doctors contracted to HMOs. Supporters said it
makes doctors battling managed care cost-cutting stronger advocates
for patient rights while opponents warned of rising health care
costs and more uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed 276-136 despite earlier approval of an
anti-abortion amendment that supporters charged was an attempt to
strip away backing from abortion rights lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   That amendment, offered by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., prohibits
discussions of abortion coverage from collective bargaining
negotiations. It passed 213-202.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation amends antitrust law to give health care
professionals the same rights enjoyed by union workers to negotiate
with health insurance plans over fees, treatments and other
contract items.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, said chief sponsor Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., is
''in favor of patients if you believe they are not being adequately
taken care of under today's medical care system because there is
not a balance between doctors and the HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the last order of business before the House left for the
weeklong July 4 recess and fulfilled a promise House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., made last year to Campbell to bring the bill to
the House floor. It was co-sponsored by Rep. John Conyers of
Michigan, senior Democrat on the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a moderate and candidate for the Senate in California,
has championed the measure in the face of opposition from GOP
leaders and the business, insurance and health care groups that
give financial backing to the party. It still faces formidable
obstacles in the GOP-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, called the bill ''the most anti-consumer piece of
legislation in decades'' and cited studies saying it would drive up
health care premiums by 8.6 percent and add 3 million to the list
of uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell said that while uniting doctors might mean less
profit for HMOs, the opposition's claims of a surge in health care
costs were exaggerated and the benefits to consumers -- from doctors
being better able to represent their interests against HMO abuses --
were far more important.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors would not be allowed to strike and the bill would
terminate after three years so its economic effects could be
analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was aided by strong sentiments among lawmakers in both
parties that Congress must act to ensure that managed care plans
don't put profits before the interests of patients. Both the House
and Senate have passed patient rights bills, but the issue of what
rights patients should have to sue HMOs has impeded efforts to come
up with a common bill.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association has strongly backed the
Campbell bill, and AMA Executive Vice President E. Ratcliff
Anderson said its passage ''will send a loud message that it is not
acceptable for big insurance companies to dictate patient medical
care in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, doctors who are employed by a hospital or
municipality may unionize and the AMA says that as of last year
about 40,000 doctors belonged to labor organizations. But most of
the nation's 650,000 doctors have been subject to anti-trust laws
that ban collective bargaining by the self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, a family physician, said his anti-abortion language was
necessary so Catholic hospitals and others with philosophical
objections wouldn't be forced to offer abortion services.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers said it was an ''anti-choice gag rule'' aimed only at
killing the bill but urged members to back the base bill in spite
of the Coburn provision.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's backers did manage to defeat several other ''poison
pill'' amendments, including one by Rep. Cass Ballenger, R-N.C.,
stating that negotiating rights not be extended to discussions of
fees. It was defeated 345-71 as several lawmakers with medical
backgrounds argued that it was impossible to improve quality care
for patients without also considering the adequacy of payments to
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   While Coburn opposed the bill on the grounds that it would drive
up health care costs, four other Republicans with medical
backgrounds, plastic surgeon Greg Ganske of Iowa, internist Dave
Weldon of Florida, OB/GYN Ron Paul of Texas and dentist Charlie
Norwood of Georgia, argued strongly for it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a mess, we have a monster we have created. All we are
asking is a little bit of return of freedom to the physician,''
Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 1304.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Bill summary: http://thomas.loc.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
