<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands Elect New PM  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- Lawmakers in the Solomon Islands
elected opposition leader Mannasseh Sogavare as the new prime
minister Friday, a move observers hope will end months of ethnic
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ''My new government will address the crisis that has been
affecting this nation this last 19 months,'' Sogavare said after
the vote, which he won 23-21. ''My government is committed to bring
Solomon Islands into national unity and reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from the former government or
from rebel groups who have been fighting on the nation's main
island, Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for rebels from Malaita island previously said his
group would accept any of the three candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Sogavare replaces ousted Prime Minister Bartholemew Ulufa'alu,
who was forced from office by the Malaitan rebels after they seized
the capital, Honiara, on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Malaitans launched the coup amid a long-running ethnic
dispute with the indigenous Isatabus of Guadalcanal, where the
capital is located.
</P>
<P>
   They were angry that the Isatabus have expelled 20,000 people
who migrated from nearby Malaita island in recent decades to find
jobs and land. Violence in recent months has killed up to 60
people.
</P>
<P>
   The Malaitan rebels control the capital while the armed Isatabu
group controls the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Friday went ahead amid tight security after a vote
scheduled for Wednesday was called off because government lawmakers
refused to attend, citing safety fears.
</P>
<P>
   All but six of Parliament's 50 legislators attended Friday's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   One of the government candidates withdrew from the election so
as not to split the government vote.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Malaitan rebels had warned that a cease-fire
that has held for more than two weeks could shatter if the
government impasse was not resolved quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the politicians are not willing to resolve the current
crisis politically, the (Malaita rebels) may pursue the military
option,'' said Andrew Nori.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
