<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Circumcision Denounced  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Female circumcision can be eradicated
within a generation, women's rights activists say, urging
governments and international organizations to move against the
practice through legislation and education.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 130 million women, most of them in Africa, have
been subjected to ritual genital cutting -- a figure that is
believed to grow by up to 2 million each year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call upon more governments, more policy-makers, and the
United Nations and other bodies to be stronger in terms of sending
the message (that) 'this is wrong,''' said Nahid Toubia, co-author
of ''Female Genital Mutilation: A Guide to Laws and Policies''
presented at U.N. headquarters on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Female genital mutilation or female circumcision can be
stopped within a generation,'' said co-author Anika Rahman of the
U.S.-based Center for Reproductive Law and Policy, a grass-roots
organization that campaigns against the practice.
</P>
<P>
   The practice is illegal in 18 countries, nine of them in Africa,
according to the research. Laws also have been passed in
industrialized countries with communities of African immigrants,
such as the United States, where a federal law bans ritual genital
cutting of females.
</P>
<P>
   Laws prohibiting the practice are not only a matter of
punishment, the activists said.
</P>
<P>
   It tells people that the country -- government and civil society
-- has decided the practice is wrong, and gives ''some power to the
people who want to say no,'' said Toubia, a doctor from Sudan,
where the practice is widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Toubia, who leads a group working on health and human rights of
African women, countered the argument that such laws go against
traditions and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before we start thinking about our communities, and our fears
for our cultures, and our fear of the disintegration of our
traditions, we have to think about one single girl. A child who is
held, scared, petrified, screaming, through a very traumatizing
experience, having a very sensitive part of her body cut,'' Toubia
said.
</P>
<P>
   Often done without anesthesia, the practice can range from
clipping or burning the clitoris to cutting off all the external
genitals and sewing the remnant tissue to leave a tiny opening.
</P>
<P>
   But laws aren't enough, Rahman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stopping female genital mutilation requires profound social
change,'' said Rahman. ''Legal change must be accompanied by public
education and other campaigns, and it must be thought in an overall
framework to promote women's rights and their status.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month at a U.N. conference to accelerate progress
toward equality for women, 180 countries called for laws to
eradicate harmful traditional practices including female
circumcision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
