<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCormick Distilling agrees to extra $1 million civil penalty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WESTON, Mo. (AP) - McCormick Distilling Co. has agreed to a $1
million civil penalty on top of $1 million in restitution already
paid to settle charges stemming from its participation in a scheme
to smuggle liquor to Eastern Europe and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The payment, along with McCormick's earlier agreement to suspend
operations for seven days beginning Saturday, is part of a
settlement resolving alleged violations of the Federal Alcohol
Administration Act.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is probably the most substantial case, in terms of the
breadth of the penalty, that we have handled in the last 20
years,'' said Jeff Cohen, assistant chief counsel with the Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. ''We consider this to have been
very serious misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, the privately owned McCormick pleaded guilty in
Newark, N.J., to a misdemeanor charge of falsifying liquor export
documents to avoid paying excise taxes overseas. Federal
authorities said the liquor, disguised as industrial alcohol, was
sold by Russian mobsters on the black market as beverage alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month McCormick paid $1 million to the Ukrainian
government to compensate it for excise taxes it was unable to
collect as a result of the smuggling scheme. The 144-year-old
company, the oldest continuously operated distillery in the
country, also agreed to pay a $10,250 criminal fine to the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCormick is now in the clear, the two-year probe into
the smuggling scheme continues. Federal authorities are focusing on
mob influence at New York shipping harbors and other distilleries.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the investigation resulted in the arrests of seven
people on money laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, all natives of former Soviet republics and most
now living in Brooklyn, N.Y., reportedly have ties to Russian
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Undercover agents approached the suspects, pretending to be
acting on behalf of big drug traffickers in Florida and South
America whose operations ''generated a lot of cash,'' in the words
of the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The agents gave cash to several of the suspects during more than
20 secretly recorded meetings at different hotel rooms. The
suspects allegedly returned the cash to the agents, less a 25
percent commission or checks payable to dummy companies formed by
the agents.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mosley, director of industrial operations in the Kansas
City field division of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms,
said he couldn't comment on the ties between the suspects and
McCormick, ''other than that product manufactured and sold by
McCormick was going into the hands of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said McCormick has cooperated in the investigation, which
also involves the FBI, the Internal Revenue Service and the Customs
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of McCormick's participation in the smuggling scheme
remains unclear, but court documents filed in New Jersey said a key
official ''within substantial authority'' at McCormick was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the U.S. attorney in Newark ''made the decision not
to prosecute any higher-ups at the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed by federal prosecutors alleged that from April
1995 to December 1997, McCormick improperly identified alcoholic
beverages shipped to Russia and Ukraine as industrial products,
using descriptive labels such as ''Cleaning,'' ''Cleansol'' and
''Rainbow Cleaning Solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The company reportedly added food coloring to the alcohol to
make it look like paint solvent, windshield washer fluid and other
industrial products. Once the alcohol was in Russia and Ukraine,
members of the Russian mob were said to have removed the food
coloring and sold the liquor on the black market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
