<HEADLINE> Boats Search for Indonesia Refugees  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANADO, Indonesia (AP) -- Dozens of local fishing boats joined
Indonesian naval vessels to search for survivors Friday after a
ship carrying nearly 500 people, including hundreds of refugees
fleeing sectarian bloodshed, vanished during a violent storm.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers scoured the waters of eastern Indonesia, looking for
any sign of wreckage or survivors, said search and rescue
coordinator Ering Musa.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing has been found so far,'' Musa said. ''There have been
no reports of survivors clinging to bits of the ship's wooden hull
or the boat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy seas and low cloud cover over the waters north of Sulawesi
island were hampering the search, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Radio contact with the Cahaya Bahari, a wooden-hulled vessel
overloaded with 492 passengers and crew, was lost Thursday after
its captain radioed that it was fast taking on water during a storm
about 1,440 miles northeast of Indonesia's capital, Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   The boat was on a journey of more than 200 miles to Manado, the
capital of North Sulawesi province, from the Maluku islands, a
corner of the Indonesian archipelago where violence between Muslims
and Christians has killed almost 3,000 people in the past 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's agent in Manado, Theddy David, said the 40-yard-long,
420-ton vessel was licensed to carry only 290 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But it was packed with frightened refugees from Duma, a
Christian village in the Malukus where more than 100 people were
killed in an attack by Muslim fighters June 19, he said. Since the
Duma attack, at least 71 people have been killed in Ambon, the
provincial capital of the Maluku islands.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic fighters say they are only standing up for the rights of
Muslims who face attacks by Christians. Muslims make up about 90
percent of Indonesia's 210 million people, but Christians are in
the majority in many parts of the Malukus.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers had been accused of doing little and of actively taking
sides in the region, known as the Moluccas or Spice Islands during
Dutch colonial days.
</P>
<P>
   After surviving the Duma massacre, the refugees took the ship
ride to be reunited with families and friends who had earlier found
shelter on Sulawesi island.
</P>
<P>
   Waters in tropical Indonesia are warm, but Musa said there were
fears for the safety of any survivors as the seas in the area are
infested with sharks. Indonesian ships of this kind rarely come
equipped with life jackets or life boats.
</P>
<P>
   The closest land is Siau island, some 40 miles to the west.
There were no immediate plans for an aerial search, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Search and rescue officials in Manado said two fishermen were
picked up Friday floating in the water after their small boat
capsized in the same storm.
</P>
<P>
   Ship disasters with large losses of life are all too frequent in
Indonesia, an ethnically and religiously diverse nation of about
17,000 islands where sea transportation is vital. Maritime
standards are lax and poorly maintained vessels are often
overloaded with passengers and cargo by captains eager to maximize
profits.
</P>
<P>
   In May, 40 people drowned after an overcrowded ferry capsized
after leaving Ambon. Last November, 361 people died when a ferry
sank off West Papua, and in February 1999, 332 people perished near
the coast of West Kalimantan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 0246 </TRAILER>
