<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 08:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Dismisses Calls To Resign  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson dismissed
calls for his resignation Friday as politics and said he will
''absolutely not'' step down over the security lapses at the Los
Alamos weapons lab.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has come under intense pressure from some members of
Congress over the two-month disappearance of two computer drives
containing nuclear secrets at Los Alamos, the lab in New Mexico
that has been embroiled in a controversy over security for much of
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on NBC's ''Today,'' Richardson said the FBI has yet
to finish its examination of the two computer drives, which
vanished from a vault and two months later were discovered behind a
copying machine in an area already searched.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson didn't learn of the incident for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, coming after repeated assurances that security
improvements were keeping nuclear materials safe, prompted Sen.
Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, and other GOP lawmakers to call for Richardson's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday about those demands, Richardson dismissed them as
political rhetoric. ''There's been politics involved,'' he said in
the NBC interview from Richland, Wash., where he flew Thursday for
a firsthand view of wildfires that threatened the Hanford nuclear
weapons site.
</P>
<P>
   ''Absolutely not,'' Richardson replied when asked if he has any
plans to resign. ''I don't walk away from a fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, although expressing deep concerns about the
security problems at Los Alamos, has repeatedly supported
Richardson and has said he continues to have confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   On another subject causing concern for the White House,
Richardson said it was a ''good sign'' that gas prices in the
Midwest have dropped in recent days from their record high levels,
but that prices don't appear to be dropping elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed part of that to a 4 percent increase in demand
this July Fourth weekend as thousands of travelers hit the
highways. Still, he said oil companies have not explained the steep
price spikes for gasoline, especially the increases in the Midwest
in the cost of cleaner-burning gasoline required in areas with
severe summertime smog.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson again said no evidence has been discovered so far to
suggest espionage was involved in the disappearance of the two Los
Alamos hard drives, which contain highly technical information on
how to dismantle an array of U.S. nuclear devices and intelligence
about some foreign nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The drives, used by a nuclear emergency response team, are
believed to have last been seen in a vault in the highly secured
''X Division'' at Los Alamos in late March. They were discovered
not far from the vault behind a copying machine on June 16 and are
being examined by the FBI to determine if any of the information
had been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said it does not appear the devices ever left the
X-Division complex, where Los Alamos scientists do their top-secret
nuclear weapons work. He said most likely ''somebody misplaced the
material and then covered up.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Richardson gave assurance that the highly radioactive
nuclear wastes, including plutonium, stored in aging gravel-covered
underground tanks at the Hanford site are safe from the fire, which
was being contained Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The fire scorched nearly half the Hanford nuclear reservation
and 20 homes as it crept within two miles of some of the area where
the nuclear wastes are located. Fire officials said Friday they
were in the process of mopping up the blaze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 0810 </TRAILER>
