<HEADLINE> Sharon Stone Appears With Dalai Lama  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sharon Stone, an outspoken advocate for the
Tibetan cause, appeared onstage with the Dalai Lama after the
dedication of a rare Tibetan mandala.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the goal of this mandala to bring peace to the hearts of
the worldwide community,'' Stone said Thursday to an audience of
more than 1,000 who gathered at Forest Lawn Memorial Park to see
the mandala and hear the teachings of the exiled Tibetan spiritual
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-year old actress, who has appeared in more than 40 films,
including ''Basic Instinct'' and ''Casino,'' laughed and joked with
the audience before leading a question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   Created by artist Pema Namdol Thaye, the mandala is a work that
represents a Tibetan art form said to be nearly extinct.
</P>
<P>
   The piece is still a work in progress and should be completed in
October. Thaye, author of the book ''Tibetan Art,'' is one of only
a handful of artists in the world still working in that style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
