<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Open Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed Friday as more companies
warned of disappointing earnings, raising fears that rising
interest rates and the slowing economy are eating away at corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the start of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 44.20 at 10,353.84, adding to
Thursday's 129-point drop.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 3.06 at 1,439.33, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 16.24 at 3,893.47.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence of a slowing economy came Friday when the Commerce
Department reported that Americans' incomes in May rose twice as
fast as their spending, pushing the nation's personal savings rate
up to its highest level since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second month in a row in which incomes rose faster
than spending and suggested that consumers may be cooling off the
buying binge of the last year. That's important because consumer
spending accounts for two-thirds of all economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Investors continue to look for signs that the economy will cool
off to a more sustainable growth rate to put a lid on inflationary
pressures and keep the Federal Reserve from boosting interest rates
at its August meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term rates six times in the past year
in an effort to keep inflation under control. On Wednesday, while
noting inflation risks continue in the economy, the Fed left
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Investors worry that additional interest rate hikes will slow
the economy to the point that corporate profits suffer. American
Financial Group Inc. warned late Thursday that its second-quarter
earnings would fall below expectations. It stock was down $1.063 at
$25.875 in early trading.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was expected to be choppy on Friday, which is the final
day of the second quarter and the day before a long weekend for
many investors who plan to skip Monday's abbreviated trading
session. U.S. financial markets will be close three hours early
Monday and close all day Tuesday for the July 4th holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1000 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 51; Nasdaq Gains 22  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Friday as more companies
warned of disappointing earnings, raising fears that rising
interest rates and the slowing economy are eating away at corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Some strength in technology stocks helped break some of the
early slide.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 51.39 at 10,346.68, adding to
Thursday's 129-point drop.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 2.12 at 1,440.27, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 22.05 at 3,899.28.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence of a slowing economy came Friday when the Commerce
Department reported that Americans' incomes in May rose twice as
fast as their spending, pushing the nation's personal savings rate
up to its highest level since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second month in a row in which incomes rose faster
than spending and suggested that consumers may be backing away from
their buying binge of the last year. That's important because
consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of all economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Investors continue to look for signs that the economy will cool
off to a more sustainable growth rate to put a lid on inflationary
pressures and keep the Federal Reserve from boosting interest rates
at its August meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term rates six times in the past year
in an effort to keep inflation under control. On Wednesday, while
noting inflation risks continue in the economy, the Fed left
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Investors worry that additional interest rate hikes will slow
the economy to the point that corporate profits suffer. In the last
few days, dozens of companies have warned of disappointing profits.
</P>
<P>
   The latest was American Financial Group Inc., which was down
43.75 cents to $26.50 after announcing that its second-quarter
earnings would fall below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   There was scattered strength among technology stocks. JDS
Uniphase rose $2.50 to $118.875 after being added to PaineWebber's
''Highlighted Stocks'' list. Other shares moving higher included
Rambus, which rose $3.0625 to $104, and Oracle, which gained $1 to
$81.875.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 117.68 million
shares, down from Thursday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was expected to remain choppy Friday, the final day of
the second quarter and the day before a long weekend for many
investors who plan to skip Monday's abbreviated trading session.
U.S. financial markets will close three hours early Monday and shut
down all of Tuesday for Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index down 0.38 at 512.20.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.37 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.28 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.55 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
