<HEADLINE> Sen. Addresses Genetic Bias Concerns  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate rejection of broad new workplace and
insurance protections against genetic discrimination, including a
right to sue, signals a go-slow approach in Congress to the
dilemmas posed by the decoding of the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   ''This issue deserves and requires a thorough discussion in its
own forum,'' Sen. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt., said, while acknowledging
that ''we need to guard genetic privacy and guard against genetic
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords, chairman of the Senate Health, Education, Labor and
Pensions Committee, promised comprehensive hearings on genetics
bias just before the Senate voted 54-44 along party lines Thursday
to defeat a Democratic measure that would have enacted a host of
new privacy protections.
</P>
<P>
   The debate followed this week's landmark announcement that
public and private researchers had essentially deciphered the
entire human genetic code, or genome. The breakthrough opens a new
universe of possibilities in preventative medicine but also raises
fears that private health information could be used to discriminate
against people prone to certain diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation the Senate rejected would have prohibited
employers from using genetic information in hiring and workplace
promotion or salaries. It also would have prevented insurance
companies from basing coverage or premiums on genetic information
and from requiring genetic tests to get coverage, and would have
permitted an individual to take discrimination claims to court.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot take one step forward in science and two steps
backward in civil rights,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D. ''Discrimination based on genetic factors is just
as unacceptable as that based on race, national origin, religion,
sex or disability.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Senate opted by a 58-40 vote for Jeffords'
alternative setting up similar restrictions on use of genetic
information by insurance companies and group health plans but doing
nothing on workplace discrimination or a right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the Democratic approach was hasty and would
result in numerous court claims.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't the right way to do it,'' said Sen. Mike Enzi,
R-Wyo. ''This becomes a turnstile for trial attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate came on amendments to the annual appropriations bill
that funds the departments of Labor, Education and Health and Human
Services. President Clinton has threatened to veto the $352 billion
spending bill -- passed by the Senate Friday on a 52-43 vote --
because of its spending levels and other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate did approve two competing ''lockbox'' provisions
aimed at preventing budget surpluses in the Medicare program from
being used for spending or tax cuts, which is similar to
legislation already passed by the House. Clinton embraced the
Democratic version.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before we make any other major budget decisions this year, we
should agree that Medicare funds should not be used to finance tax
cuts or other spending,'' the president said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also attached legislation -- criticized by Democrats
-- giving 56 million people limited new medical rights, such as
access to emergency room care and to out-of-network physicians.
People also would have a restricted right to sue their HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton announced before the overall spending bill even
reached the Senate floor that he would veto it, contending it would
not reduce classroom sizes by providing money he wants to hire
100,000 new teachers and would not guarantee $1.3 billion in loans
and grants to repair crumbling schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last week also added another provision opposed by the
administration that would block Labor Department rules giving
workers new protections against repetitive motion injuries.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4577.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1128 </TRAILER>
