<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA, Customs To Check for Fireworks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal inspectors will be screening airline
passengers' baggage for fireworks over the holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   All types of fireworks are banned from aircraft, either in
checked or carry-on bags.
</P>
<P>
   The inspections will be handled by agents of the Federal
Aviation Administration and Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even the smallest sparklers could be deadly if they ignited
during flight, and they are all strictly prohibited,'' said Cathal
L. Flynn, associate FAA administrator for security.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said bags will be selected at random for screening at
airports across the country. No delays are expected due to the
increased scrutiny, but the FAA reminded passengers that they
should arrive at least one hour early for domestic flights and two
hours early for international flights.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said fireworks are a concern around Independence Day
every year since most of the annual sales of these goods take place
in June and July. Persons caught with fireworks on aircraft can be
subject to fines and jail time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
