<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Castro Enjoying Recent Victories  </HEADLINE>
By ANITA SNOW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- His eyes wide and a smile dancing behind his
grizzled beard, Fidel Castro looked like a friendly grandfather,
moving his head back and forth as dozens of youngsters sang a song
about childhood happiness dedicated to Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The private reunion between Castro and a select group of
children after a march last month of up to 200,000 boys and girls
showed a man who had won important victories during the seven-month
campaign to bring Elian home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by the kind of young people he hopes will carry on
his revolutionary ideals, Cuba's usually stiff maximum leader even
moved his lips in the videotape shown on state television, singing
along as a young boy clasped his hand and a little girl with a
booming voice warbled into a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are thousands like you,'' the 73-year-old leader told
the children, ''Dozens of thousands. Hundreds of thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro was not physically present for Elian's return Wednesday,
and it's unknown if he has visited with the boy and his family
since then. The Cuban leader has worked to ensure that neither he
nor the Cuban people appear vainglorious over the boy's
repatriation.
</P>
<P>
   But even before Elian's return, the man described here these
days as ''our unconquerable commander in chief'' had already made
significant political gains.
</P>
<P>
   For perhaps the first time during his 41 years in power, most
Americans found themselves in agreement with Castro on an issue.
They agreed that the 6-year-old boy belonged with his father, even
if it meant they would live in communist Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Since shortly after Elian was rescued off Florida's coast in
late November, polls consistently showed Americans siding with
Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans also approved of the U.S. government's armed raid
that forcibly removed Elian from his Miami relatives' home April 22
and reunited him with his dad, according to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the legal battle over Elian put Cuba on the
front page of U.S. newspapers and at the top of evening broadcasts,
creating new interest in an island that for decades was a mystery
to many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Cuban-Americans, who have strong opinions stemming from
often dramatic personal experience, the case showed that 10 years
after the collapse of the former Soviet Union most Americans no
longer view Cuba in strictly ideological terms.
</P>
<P>
   And as they learned more about Cuba, Americans increasingly
questioned the nearly four-decade U.S. embargo against the
Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. lawmakers in early June moved toward at least a partial
lifting of the trade sanctions. House Republicans, in an
unprecedented move, this week agreed to lift U.S. restrictions on
sales of food and medicine to Cuba provided they are not financed
by either the federal government or private U.S. sources.
</P>
<P>
   And while American public opinion in the case weighed in
Castro's favor, the exiles he refers to as the Miami ''mafia'' --
who staged noisy protests insisting that Elian stay in the United
States -- were marginalized.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Castro used the battle to whip up patriotic fervor
among the population at large while sparking new political interest
and leadership among Cuba's children and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   While some Cubans admitted privately they had wearied of the
almost daily protests and television shows dedicated to Elian,
virtually all say that the child belonged at home with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The battle especially affected young people, who identified with
the story of the little boy who lost his mother at sea and was
separated from his father.
</P>
<P>
   Very young children were delighted with the packages distributed
at schools that contained heartwarming photographs of Elian and his
father after their reunion in the United States. They came in a box
imprinted with Castro's signature.
</P>
<P>
   When he launched the national campaign of mass mobilizations
back in early December, Castro promised that the nation's young
people would be the protagonists.
</P>
<P>
   After a virulent speech about ''anti-imperialism'' at an April
rally, Lazaro Castro, a bespectacled fourth grader, ran from the
stage to embrace the Cuban president.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy so impressed officials that he was invited to
speak again at the children's march and to attend the private
reunion with Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are the seeds of the great revolution!'' little Lazaro
cried during the private meeting with Castro. ''Commander in chief!
At your orders!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1527 </TRAILER>
