<DOCNO> APW20000630.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donations Track Doctor Bill Votes  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House lawmakers who voted against letting
doctors collectively bargain with HMOs got twice as much in
campaign donations from the industry as those who sided with
physicians, an Associated Press analysis shows.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, those who voted in favor of the doctors got about 25
percent more in donations from physicians than their opposing
colleagues, the analysis found.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation allowing the collective bargaining passed early
Friday, 276-136.
</P>
<P>
   The case illustrates how lawmakers' votes often coincide with
the interests of those who pay for their campaigns, said Larry
Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics,
a nonpartisan research group that keeps an eye on money and
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the other side of money and politics,'' Makinson said.
''People don't give money without getting results.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would amend antitrust law to give health care
professionals the same rights enjoyed by union workers to negotiate
with health insurance plans over fees, treatments and other
contract items. Doctors would not be allowed to strike and the bill
would terminate after three years so its economic effects could be
analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the doctors' legislation is part of a broader
election-year push to give patients more rights in dealing with
cost-conscious HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the bill would give doctors more leverage to
battle cost-cutting by managed care operators while opponents
contended it could lead to rising health care costs and decisions
by HMOs to drop coverage for some Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation still faces formidable obstacles in the
GOP-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have donated heavily to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall since Jan. 1, 1999, doctors contributed $4 million to
House members, while HMOs doled out $301,369.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's chief sponsor, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., had
accused his GOP colleagues of delaying a vote so they could
continue collecting money from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said, 'Don't force me to choose between two potential
contributors.... Just delay it so we can milk both cows,'''
Campbell said in May.
</P>
<P>
   The 136 lawmakers who voted against the bill averaged $1,084 in
contributions from HMOs and company officials, according to an AP
analysis of campaign data from the Center for Responsive Politics.
The 276 House members who supported the bill averaged $496 in HMO
contributions, the analysis found.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five biggest recipients of HMO donations, only one, Rep.
Jim Gibbons, R-Nev., voted for the legislation. He received
$12,349.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., who voted against the legislation,
had the most in HMO contributions at $19,000. She sits on the
health panel of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, supporters of the bill to allow collective
bargaining averaged $9,915 in contributions from doctors, compared
with an average of $7,893 for opponents, the analysis showed.
</P>
<P>
   The five lawmakers who raised the most money from doctors voted
for the bill, led by Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, a
surgeon-turned-congressman who received $73,550 from fellow
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the American Medical Association's board of trustees
suggested the HMOs should have spent their donations on something
other than an effort to block the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The money they have spent, I imagine we might not have needed
a Campbell bill if they spent it on patient care,'' said Dr. Donald
Palmisano, a New Orleans surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Merritt, a vice president for the American Association of
Health Plans, said the HMO trade group was simply fighting back
against better-financed opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the face of this kind of money politics, you have to do
something to defend yourselves and the interests of consumers,''
Merritt said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality of this is money won, consumers lost, health care
lost, and policy was made on the altar of special-interest politics
to benefit a small elite group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmisano said the AMA encourages doctors to donate to
congressional candidates, saying, ''We tell them to get involved in
campaigns and to help support people who have good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 1304.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   American Medical Association: http://www.ama-assn.org
</P>
<P>
   American Association of Health Plans: http://www.aahp.org
</P>
<P>
   Center for Responsive Politics: http://www.opensecrets.org
</P>
