<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton addresses health care graduates at SUNY-Stony Brook  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONY BROOK, N.Y. (AP) - Donning her figurative first-lady hat
and a graduation gown, Hillary Rodham Clinton told SUNY-Stony Brook
graduates Friday they are among the first health care professionals
who will be able to beat diseases like cancer, Parkinson's or
Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll actually be professionals at a time when it is not
futile or unrealistic to hope that children at the end of this
century will have to look in history books to learn about diseases
that plague us and kill today,'' Clinton told graduates of the
School of Health, Technology and Management.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate against
Republican Rick Lazio, spoke to the health care graduates in her
role as first lady, although she touched on many of the same issues
mentioned during her stump speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Politics aside, ''This day is really about the students,'' noted
Pete Gillen of Shirley, who graduated with a degree in occupational
therapy. But ''I'm grateful that she could share it with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said: ''The future of our health care system will be
determined in large measure by the decisions that we make over the
next few years.'' She said scientific and technological advances,
such has the mapping of the human genetic code, also create ethical
dilemmas for many in the health care field.
</P>
<P>
   ''What good would the best genetic tests in the world be if
people are too worried to use them?'' she asked. ''I think it is
long past time, and it is certainly urgent, that we now outlaw
genetic discrimination, so that our genes and the information
derived from them are used to heal us, not deny us jobs or health
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said ''it is time that our medical records have just as
much protection as the records of our video store rentals do right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who headed the Clinton administration's failed
efforts to overhaul the health care system, also said the
scientific advances should be accompanied by ways to ''finance our
health care system in a way that is fair and provides the support
that everyone should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for a ''patients bill of rights that puts
people back in charge of their health care,'' and urged that
prescription drugs be made affordable for all patients.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday, Clinton echoed the theme in a Manhattan speech to
the American Association of Physicians of Indian Origin.
</P>
<P>
   ''One reason why I support the Democratic version of the
patients bill of rights is because I want doctors making decisions
about my health care, and not some bureacrat in an office a
thousand miles away,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 1528 </TRAILER>
