<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Turnout in Iran Run-Off Votes  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Turnout appeared low in Tehran's legislative
runoff elections, held Friday to fill two seats for which
first-round reformist victories were annulled by the hard-line
election council.
</P>
<P>
   The two vacant seats in greater Tehran were being contested by
four pro-reform candidates who narrowly missed victory in the
February polls. Turnout was light because of the absence of
conservative candidates in the mix. Results were expected to be
announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm here to show my continuing support for reforms, although
these elections are not significant because only reformists are
vying for the seats,'' Ali Rezai, 38, said after casting his vote.
''I believe if we don't turn out, then the conservatives will
become bolder in their anti-reform attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   President Mohammad Khatami, whose reforms have been opposed by
hard-liners, urged residents to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Parliamentary elections are very important in a country run by
the people and in view of the balancing role played by the Majlis
(parliament) and its supervision over power,'' Khatami said after
voting early Friday in northern Tehran, according to the official
Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Reformists won about three-quarters of parliament's 290 seats in
the Feb. 18 polls, putting them in control of the legislature for
the first time since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, reformists initially were said to have won 29 of
the 30 seats, but the supervisory Guardian Council delayed
endorsing the results for three months, alleging fraud. The council
finally confirmed the Tehran results, but said reformists had won
26 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The council awarded two seats to hard-liners, including one to
former president Hashemi Rafsanjani, and annulled the results in
two other seats.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four candidates competing Friday was Ali Akbar
Mohtashami-Pour, publisher of the reformist newspaper Bayan that
was recently closed by the hard-line judiciary. In the struggle
between conservatives and moderates, hard-liners have shut down 19
pro-reform newspapers and jailed several reformist editors and
political activists in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, was among those
who voted early Friday in central Tehran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
