<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DC Mayor Defends Government Reform  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER ANDES
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House lawmakers urged Mayor Anthony A.
Williams on Friday to push harder to reform a District of Columbia
government damaged by previous administrations and to do a better
job balancing city finances.
</P>
<P>
   ''Boldness is what we need,'' said Rep. Ernest Istook, Jr.,
R-Okla., chairman of the Appropriations subcommittee on the
District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Istook questioned why Williams has not replaced agency leaders
who are resisting reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can change those people,'' Istook said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he initiated a six-month review in June intended
to hold agency leaders accountable and that he wants to give people
a fair basis for evaluation. As the District's chief financial
officer, Williams fired 165 city workers for incompetence and found
himself embroiled in controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been criticized in the past,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who do not meet performance goals may accept an
early retirement plan intended in part as a cost-savings measure,
Williams said. The goal is to reduce the government work force by
1,000 full-time employees this year at a savings of $37 million, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make sure those savings happen,'' Istook said.
</P>
<P>
   Istook and Rep. James P. Moran, D-Va., questioned the city's
ability to monitor savings and reform efforts in light of a General
Accounting Office report issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The report focused on $330 million spent on 280 management
reform programs intended to save $200 million and improve the
quality of service to residents over the past three years. It found
that just 69 of the 280 projects were completed or showed results
and that the District has reported savings of just $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a pretty sad effort at management reform,'' Moran said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
