<HEADLINE> Agreements From U.N. Poverty Summit  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The following are some of the ''further actions and
initiatives'' agreed by the special session of the U.N. General
Assembly on poverty reduction.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agreement:
</P>
<P>
   -- Sets a target to halve the number of people living in extreme
poverty by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   -- Stresses that achieving education for all will require an
extra $8 billion annually, and calls on donors to increase their
financial commitments to development assistance and debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   -- Agrees to defend and promote the interests of developing
countries in international economic and trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   -- Makes a commitment to protect basic social services,
especially health and education, when dealing with international
financial crises.
</P>
<P>
   -- Presses employers and companies to understand that they have a
responsibility to promote social development and growth.
</P>
<P>
   -- Calls on governments to reassess economic policies to balance
the goal of employment creation better against that of maintaining
low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   -- Encourages debt relief initiatives by creditor countries and
impresses on debtors that the money released should be used for
development, including poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
   -- Calls on the United Nations to launch a global campaign to
eradicate poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
