<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Dept. Urges Dialogue in China  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department again urged peaceful
dialogue between China and Taiwan on Friday but avoided any
commentary on the latest statements over the possibility of
establishing a single China.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's up to Beijing and Taipei to determine when they have the
basis for the dialogue,'' said spokesman Richard Boucher. He urged
both sides to show more flexibility in their disagreement on
Chinese sovereignty over Taiwan, which broke away from the mainland
in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian on Tuesday said he could
accept a 1992 deal with China that Taiwanese believe would allow
both sides to interpret ''one China'' in its own way. But China on
Friday accused Chen of betraying hopes for improved relations by
refusing to flatly acknowledge that Taiwan is part of Chinese
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher reiterated U.S. support for one China under the
government in Beijing and said the United States remains
''committed to promoting peace, stability and prosperity'' in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our abiding interest is in a peaceful resolution of the
differences between the two sides, and we will certainly continue
to advocate that and to welcome any steps that would foster
dialogue, but also urge the parties to refrain from any actions
that would increase tensions in the region,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial distributed by China's official Xinhua News Agency
accused Chen of distorting the 1992 agreement by claiming that the
sides had agreed to interpret ''one China'' differently. Beijing
says both sides in agreed to adhere to the ''one-China principle''
but there was no actual discussion of what ''one China'' means.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has been suspicious of Chen because his party advocates
Taiwan's formal and permanent independence from China, not eventual
unification.
</P>
<P>
   The sides have been at odds since the communist takeover of the
mainland 51 years ago, and China still threatens to use force to
unify itself with Taiwan if necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
