<HEADLINE> Eminem: Fame Turning Into Nightmare  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Rap star Eminem says that for years he longed for
the kind of fame he enjoys today. Now he's not so sure he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost turning into more of a nightmare than a dream,''
he told the Detroit Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem, the 27-year-old artist who was born as Marshall Mathers
III, faces gun charges in Royal Oak and Warren. He also faces a
civil suit by a man who says Eminem attacked him while carrying a
gun.
</P>
<P>
   ''I miss going to the park and playing basketball,'' he said.
''I was never that person who wanted the big cars and (Mercedes)
Benzes. All I really wanted was to have a career in hip-hop.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Eminem won Grammys for his debut album, ''The Slim
Shady LP,'' and its hit single ''My Name Is.'' His new album, ''The
Marshall Mathers LP,'' has gone platinum, with sales of 4 million
in its first five weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
