<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. man makes bail in dancer's death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - John Denofa, the Buckingham, Pa.,
businessman charged with killing an exotic dancer, posted a
$500,000 bond Friday and was released, according to the Burlington
County prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Denofa, 35, had been in jail on a $1 million bond after he was
charged with the death of 21-year-old Rachel Siani. Her body was
found April 1 under a bridge that connects the New Jersey and
Pennsylvania turnpikes.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Superior Court Judge John A. Sweeney in Mount Holly
agreed to reduce Denofa's bond during a recent hearing, at which
more than 20 of Denofa's friends and relatives appeared on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his release Friday, Denofa had to sign an affidavit not
to fight extradition and a form promising he would not apply for a
passport, said First Assistant Burlington County Prosecutor Raymond
Milavsky.
</P>
<P>
   Siani worked at Divas International Gentleman's Club in Bristol
Township, Pa. The Bensalem, Pa., resident was last seen with Denofa
March 29 in the club's parking lot, according to police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
