<HEADLINE> Russia Claims Victory Over Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- A top Russian general on Friday said
troops had annihilated a band of Chechen rebels after a five-day
firefight in the southern mountains, while another shootout
reportedly erupted in Chechnya's capital, Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Gen. Gennady Troshev said the fighting near the southern
town of Serzhen-Yurt was over, and that the rebel band had been
''annihilated.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting underscored that Chechnya remains restive, despite
repeated Russian claims that the nine-month war is over.
</P>
<P>
   As that battle wound down, clashes erupted Friday in a forest
just south of Grozny after soldiers discovered rebels preparing an
ambush, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Boxed in by forests on both sides of a highway, the ambushed
troops opened fire at the trees with grenade launchers and
heavy-caliber machine guns, but were unsure if they hit any rebels,
the report said, citing an Interfax correspondent at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about 21 miles to the south, Russian soldiers began
searching through dense greenery near Serzhen-Yurt, where fighting
raged this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''A mopping-up operation is under way in the area, and the
situation is on the whole under control,'' Troshev said, according
to ITAR-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television showed dead bodies on the forest floor, which
had been pounded for three days by Russian artillery, machine guns,
grenades and aerial bombs and rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman on Chechnya Sergei Yastrzhembsky said
Friday that troops had found fresh graves, and ''on the ground
fragments of the bodies of over 40 fighters were strewn.''
</P>
<P>
   Troshev said more than 100 rebels had been killed, but the claim
could not be confirmed. Russian officials often overstate enemy
losses.
</P>
<P>
   One Russian serviceman was killed Friday and six were wounded in
the area when their army truck was ambushed. After a mine
explosion, rebels opened fire, according to one soldier who was
interviewed by NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   At least 12 Russian soldiers were killed at Serzhen-Yurt earlier
this week. Serzhen-Yurt lies at the head of the Vedeno Gorge, a key
rebel refuge in the southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Chechnya on Friday, Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev said the rebel group near Serzhen-Yurt had planned to
attack Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city and used as the
administrative seat for a pro-Moscow government.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic leader Akhmad Kadyrov, the Chechen head of the
pro-Moscow administration, said Friday he hoped to meet with
President Vladimir Putin next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a very serious issue that can only be settled at the
level of the Russian president, and Vladimir Putin should make a
decision on it personally,'' Kadyrov told journalists in Grozny,
according to Interfax. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Continued fighting has deterred most refugees from returning,
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said Friday in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   About 170,000 refugees remain in the neighboring republic of
Ingushetia, and many are likely to remain through next winter,
UNHCR spokesman Ron Redmond said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war with
independence fighters. They went back in September, after
Chechnya-based Islamic militants raided several villages in the
neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and after about 300 people
died in apartment bombings the government blamed on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
