<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Driver Cell Phones Banned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong drivers will no longer be allowed to
use hand-held cellular phones while on the road after a new law
goes into effect this weekend, a transport official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Saturday, drivers face a $256 fine if caught holding a
cell phone while driving, Transport Bureau spokeswoman Joyce Yip
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, they can still use so-called ''handsfree devices,''
such as headphones and speaker phones, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mobile phones are very popular here, but drivers get
distracted when they're talking on the phone. It affects their
driving performance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Data from other countries show that cell phone use contributes
to a higher accident rate, but Hong Kong hasn't kept such
statistics, Yip said.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are ubiquitous in this Asian financial hub. About 65
percent of the population -- 4.47 million people -- use cell phones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
