<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax breaks on gas, clothing go on books Saturday  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Connecticut drivers are promised a break
at the gas pump and shoppers will pick up a few bargains when new
tax cuts go on the books Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's gasoline tax - the highest in the country next to
Hawaii - will be rolled back 7 cents to a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Gas station owners will be required to pass the savings on to
customers. And the state's consumer protection chief says he'll be
keeping a watchful eye.
</P>
<P>
   ''State inspectors will be out making sure the prices reflect
the tax cut,'' Consumer Protection Commissioner James Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   If drivers suspect they're being fleeced at the filling station,
they can call make a toll-free phone call to the consumer
protection hotline at 1-800-842-2649.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a few days for some stations to comply with the
lower prices - they're allowed to sell off any gasoline they
already have in their tanks at the 32-cent tax rate. But once they
get new shipments, the prices must come down. If they don't decline
within the next 120 days, station owners can be slapped with a $500
fine and a 6-month prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Legislature has put some teeth in this cut,'' Fleming
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the 4-month inspection period, gas station owners will be
required to account for price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fox, executive director of the Gasoline &AMP; Automotive
Service Dealers of America, said he doesn't expect pump prices to
skyrocket after the 120 day inspection period - unless wholesalers
drive up the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the prices go up, it won't be happening from our end,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland, who pushed for the 7-cent reduction during
this year's legislative session despite initial resistance from
Democratic leaders, says the tax break will save $85 to $140 a year
for a family that drives 30,000 miles. Making Connecticut's gas
prices competitive with border states will also keep drivers from
spending their money across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping will also be a little easier on residents' wallets. The
sales tax on clothing and footwear is being lifted on items priced
up to $75 - that's an increase from the $50 tax exemption.
</P>
<P>
   And clothing that costs less than $300 will be tax-free during
the third week of August, an incentive aimed at back-to-school
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Child car seats, college textbooks, and items bought from
vending machines that cost less than 50 cents also will no longer
be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   And automobiles with a federal Environmental Protection Agency
rating of 50 miles per gallon will be driving off the lots tax
free. Currently, the only vehicles with such fuel efficiency are
cars that are powered with a combination of gasoline and
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ''That tax exemption gives people an incentive to try the new
technology,'' said Ellen Schneider, a spokeswoman from the
Department of Revenue Services. ''It could save people thousands of
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday also ushers in a tax cut for movie tickets costing more
than $5. The current 10 percent tax is being whittled down 8
percent during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Saturday, the state will start making more grants
available to school districts trying to put more computer
technology in classrooms, and the tax on computer data processing
services will drop from 3 percent to 2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
