<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dumping Nuke Waste Into Sea Banned  </HEADLINE>
By JAN M. OLSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- A European conference on protecting
the northeastern Atlantic Ocean's maritime environment has banned
nuclear reprocessing plants from discharging waste into the sea,
but the decision won't apply to France and Britain -- the only two
countries in the region to have such plants.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the discharges banned by the OSPAR accord come from
three nuclear reprocessing plants -- Sellafield and Dounreay in
Britain, and La Hague in France.
</P>
<P>
   The ban was largely symbolic, since France and Britain abstained
and so were not legally bound by the vote. But environmental
leaders said they hoped the two countries would get the message.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is an amicable signal (to France and Britain). It is not
a start of hostility,'' said Danish Environment Minister Svend
Auken, who hosted the five-day conference attended by the 16
countries that are part of the OSPAR convention, which protects
waters that stretch from the Arctic Circle in the north to Portugal
on Europe's southwestern tip.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve OSPAR members voted in favor of the accord, providing the
necessary three-quarters approval to make it legally binding. No
time frame was provided for ultimately eliminating the waste
discharges into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Reprocessing nuclear waste involves removing unused uranium or
plutonium from spent fuel rods for reuse at energy plants. Auken
said the practice posed ''a major risk for accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, a British government report said workers at
Sellafield deliberately falsified records relating to the quality
of fuel pellets. The plant was shut down until the problem was
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that security work is sloppy,'' Auken said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace, which had observer status at the meeting, welcomed
the accord. ''It's a defeat for nuclear reprocessing industry,''
International Political Director Remi Parmentier said.
</P>
<P>
   OSPAR has already banned dumping of nuclear waste from ships,
platforms and aircraft into waters that stretch from the northern
Arctic Circle to Portugal on Europe's southwestern tip.
</P>
<P>
   Other OSPAR members are Belgium, Finland, Germany, Iceland,
Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Sweden and
Switzerland, the European Union and Luxembourg, which was absent
from the vote on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
