<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Crumple Zone' Exploits Cantone  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0881-----
r e *1404AP-Theater-Crumple     06-30 0512
*1404 AP-Theater-Crumple-Zone,0512   
'Crumple Zone' Exploits Cantone   
An AP Entertainment Review
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nobody does comic agitation better than Mario
Cantone.
</P>
<P>
   The man can work himself up to considerable grief -- part nasal
whine, part shriek, part diva-like dementia -- that rarely fails to
produce a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, Cantone, a short guy with big talent, has to do
all the work in ''The Crumple Zone,'' an artificial gay comedy now
playing at off-Broadway's Rattlestick Theater. The play by Buddy
Thomas exploits its leading man without offering him much support.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is Staten Island at Christmas, a place and time
guaranteed to bring out the worst in people. Out-of-work actor
Terry, played by Cantone, hates the holiday, hates his job as a
waiter in a Mafia-owned diner, but, most of all, hates the fact
that he is not in a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Terry mopes and moons over Buck, a lanky fellow who seems intent
on busting up the romance between Terry's roommate, Alex, and Matt,
an actor out on the road in a tour of Stephen King's ''Salem's
Lot'' -- the musical.
</P>
<P>
   Terry, of course, is a hopeless romantic, despite a vicious
tongue and a propensity to solve every problem with a bottle of
Absolut. He believes that even if the course of true love never
runs smooth, it should not be allowed to detour.
</P>
<P>
   Cantone, at least, gives his character some depth, a quality the
other actors in the production have not been able to do. But then,
Cantone has the best lines in the play. He has some wonderfully
dizzy physical moments, too.
</P>
<P>
   Watch him try to get out from under a Christmas tree, which has
toppled to the ground during one of the comedy's more emotional
moments. Or lip-synching to a smashing rendition by Debbie Gravitte
of the old Kalmar and Ruby standard, ''Nevertheless I'm in Love
with You.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' comedy teeters between sporadically amusing farce and
unconvincing soap opera. Cantone provides the looniness, the other
actors the suds. Director Jason Moore keeps the convoluted story
moving at a reasonable clip, wisely getting the other actors out of
the way when Cantone takes over.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, ''The Crumple Zone,'' which during the course of
its two short acts verges on the saccharine, pulls away from a
predictable happy ending. And it's Cantone's character who gets to
deliver the common-sense advice.
</P>
<P>
   The play's title, according to program notes, is an automotive
term: ''an area of a car designed to compress during an accident to
absorb the energy from impact.'' The author seems to be saying that
everyone needs a crumple zone to cushion the crashes that threaten
to cause serious emotional or physical injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Cantone has had several notable roles in the past, replacing
Nathan Lane in ''Love! Valour! Compassion!'' and Bill Irwin when
the Patrick Stewart ''Tempest'' moved from Central Park to
Broadway. Now someone needs to showcase his talents in a strong new
play. ''The Crumple Zone'' isn't it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1627 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few Celebrate Congo Independence  </HEADLINE>
By KAMANGA MUTOND
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Few celebrated as Congo marked 40 years
of independence from Belgium on Friday with military bands and a
parade in a country ravaged by years of corruption and civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of soldiers and civilians, some dressed in the colors
of the flag, marched to the beat of military bands down a central
boulevard decorated with pots of flowers, as President Laurent
Kabila and Belgian Prime Minister Louis Michel looked on.
</P>
<P>
   But many in this vast Central African nation avoided the
festivities and went about their ordinary activities, or just
stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese newspapers were critical of the festivities, with the
opposition Le Potentiel describing the past 40 years as ''a
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Congo was ruined by decades of government neglect and corruption
under the late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, who became one of the
world's richest men by plundering the vast mineral wealth of the
country, then known as Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila was welcomed as a liberator when his army swept across
the country in eight months in 1997. But a year later, he faced a
rebellion launched by Congolese Tutsis, disaffected soldiers and
opposition politicians who accused him of mismanagement, corruption
and warmongering.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the misery of Congo's impoverished citizens has only
increased. Hospitals don't have medicine. Schools have shut down.
Roads -- if they exist at all -- are unusable through large parts of
the interior.
</P>
<P>
   A cease-fire agreement was signed July 10 by Kabila and his
allies -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- and by Rwanda and Uganda,
who are backing the rebels. The main rebel factions signed on in
the weeks that followed.
</P>
<P>
   But fighting has continued, with all sides accusing each other
of violations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Kabila said he was pleased ''the people have
resisted aggression and managed to celebrate the 40th anniversary
of independence.''
</P>
<P>
   ''But we have to look to the future with greater optimism,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Congo was founded in the late 19th century as the personal
property of Belgium's King Leopold II. The Belgian government took
control in 1908, and the country's colonial rulers withdrew in 1960
following massive pro-independence riots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1627 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
