<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Jews Pray for Accused Spies  </HEADLINE>
By AFSHIN VALINEJAD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran (AP) -- Iranian Jews converged Friday on a synagogue
in the heart of this ancient city's Jewish quarter, offering
prayers on the eve of a verdict for 13 Jews accused of spying for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to pray sincerely for tomorrow, and whatever happens
I accept that it is God's will,'' said Daniel Bent-Yacoub, the
14-year-old son of Javid Bent-Yacoub. Defense attorneys have said
Daniel's father, a 42-year-old shop owner, testified to collecting
military information for Israel but insisted his actions weren't
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 people -- only men and boys to avoid overcrowding --
attended the prayers at Rabeezadeh Synagogue. Because of the Jewish
Sabbath, all the men arrived on foot for the prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother is at home,'' Daniel said. ''She prefers to pray in
solitude. She's quite anxious, but hopeful for God's mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women relatives of the defendants came after the prayers to
offer one another support. They hugged each other and said they
were praying for the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The case has cast a pall over the 6,000-strong Jewish community
of Shiraz, the ancient capital of the Persian empire that attracted
people of all faiths because of its wealth and tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 13 Jewish defendants have pleaded guilty, four have
pleaded innocent and one -- Bent-Yacoub -- acknowledged passing
information but maintains his action did not constitute espionage.
Israel has denied any of the 13 were spies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, two Jews were hanged at Tehran's Evin prison on similar
spying charges. Iranian officials have differed on whether the
death penalty could be applied if any of the 13 in the current case
are convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the imprisoned Jews has attracted attention from
the United States, Israel and several European countries, which
have demanded Iran free the suspects. Representatives of the Dutch
and Canadian embassies were in Shiraz to await the verdict;
Japanese and Australian officials were expected Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's Jewish community, although it has dwindled over the
decades, remains the Middle East's largest outside Israel. Iranian
Jews are allowed to practice aspects of their religion but are
forbidden to teach Hebrew, the liturgical language.
</P>
<P>
   At its height, Iran's Jewish community numbered about 100,000
and was still around 80,000 just before Iran's 1979 Islamic
revolution. Now there are about 25,000 Jews. Among those attending
the prayers Friday were Haroun Yashayaii, head of Iran's Jewish
society and Maurice Moatamed, the single Jewish representative in
the 290-seat Majlis, or parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1630 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Sailors' Kin Seek Damages  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Relatives of 323 Argentine
sailors who died when the British sank their ship during the 1982
Falklands Islands war will seek damages from England in an
international court, their lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers representing the families of sailors aboard the
warship Belgrano said Thursday they would press their case next
week before the International Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg,
France.
</P>
<P>
   The sinking of the Belgrano marked the turning point in the
10-week war. Battling in the South Atlantic Ocean, the warship
British Conqueror torpedoed the Belgrano.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, Jorge Appiani and Jorge Antonio Olivera, contend
the sinking violated wartime conventions set by the Hague in 1907
because it occurred beyond the 200-mile limit of the theater of
operations designated by Britain.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response to those claims.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina contends it inherited the islands, which it calls the
Malvinas and where about 2,200 people of mostly British ancestry
live, from the Spanish crown before they were occupied by Britain
in 1833.
</P>
<P>
   The Falklands war -- won by Britain in 74 days -- claimed at least
970 lives and helped hasten the departure of Argentina's military
government of the era.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina never sought damages against England after the war.
After nearly a decade of icy relations, the two countries restored
diplomatic relations in 1990, although Argentina still maintains
its claim to the islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1632 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall approves Medicaid provider contract extension despite doubts </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - State Comptroller H. Carl McCall Friday
approved a two-year contract extension between the state and
Maximus Inc. despite his ''serious concerns'' about the company's
Medicaid managed care enrollment work.
</P>
<P>
   The $43 million contract amendments call for Maximus to continue
handling Medicaid managed care enrollments for the state Health
Department in New York City, and to extend the program to Nassau
and Suffolk counties on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The state's current contract with Maximus was to expire at
midnight Friday. It was signed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said his review of the contract extension raised
questions in his mind of how accurate the information was which the
company was providing to Medicaid recipients. Those same concerns
were raised in 1999 by Mark Green, New York City's public advocate.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said he was also troubled that as of earlier this month,
information about Medicaid managed care was not available from
Maximus in languages other than English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 670,000 people currently enrolled in Medicaid
managed care in New York state, about 390,000 in New York City.
State Health Commissioner Dr. Antonia Novello says she wants to
expand enrollments to 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau and Suffolk county enrollments are currently handled by
local social services officials.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus is not providing health care coverage or services in New
York, but is finding eligible Medicaid recipients and enrolling
them in managed care.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department is confident Maximus can do the job its
contract calls for and has been pleased with the responsiveness of
the company when problems or concerns have been pointed out,
department spokesman John Signor said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to monitor and oversee Maximus operations as
we always have to ensure a Medicaid recipient receives quality
health care in managed care,'' Signor said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman added that Health Department officials were
''amazed'' that McCall continues to raise concerns about Maximus
since the department believes it answered them months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are really old issues,'' Signor said. ''They have mostly
been taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Maximus, based in McLean, Va., is currently embroiled in a court
battle in New York City over the awarding of more than $100 million
in city welfare-to-work contracts to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus is the nation's largest operator of welfare-to-work
programs for state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the company Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
