<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Power reliability still at risk this summer  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Those summer ''power watch'' alerts will
likely be common again this summer, since many of the problems that
caused problems last year have not been remedied, state regulators
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Stresses on the power system will not be alleviated until new
power plants and transmission systems are built in the state, the
Department of Public Utility Control said Thursday in a draft
report.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is still a risk of significant shortfall in supply over
the next few summers,'' the DPUC said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also chronicles the reasons for last summer's power
problems, which got so bad on one day in June that the governors of
Connecticut, Massachusetts and Rhode Island shut down state
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ISO-New England, which manages the region's power system, said
it has put new programs and regulations in place to improve
reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Power watches will remain one way of reducing electricity demand
on hot, summer days when utilities have to dip into power reserves,
said ISO-New England spokesman Jim Sinclair. In issuing the alerts,
utilities ask consumers to voluntarily shut off unneeded
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would like nothing more than to have more generation for
summer than we had,'' Sinclair said. ''What we're projecting is six
to nine days this summer, when we'll have to go into that reserve
tank, and three or four times we'll be looking to the public to
keep that reserve tank full.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's an improved situation over last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, ISO-New England has set up contracts where
companies would be paid to reduce their power use in emergencies.
Also, because of unexpected hot weather in June for the past few
years, power plants are now not supposed to schedule outages that
month.
</P>
<P>
   ISO-New England and the DPUC agree, however, that the power
watches and other measures to conserve in high-demand times are
symptomatic of stresses on the system.
</P>
<P>
   The DPUC will take testimony from ISO-New England, utilities and
other groups before issuing a final report, scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers plan to review the report this summer to see
what policy changes may be possible to improve electric
reliability, said Rep. Kevin DelGobbo of Naugatuck, the ranking
Republican on the Energy and Technology Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In its 68-page report, the DPUC points out that Connecticut's
power situation has changed from several years ago, when power
scarcity was rare.
</P>
<P>
   Two nuclear power plants, Connecticut Yankee and Millstone Unit
1, are shut down and being decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   While companies in Wallingford, Killingly, Oxford and Milford
plan to build new power plants, none of the plants is yet running,
and some may never be built because of local conflicts, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's ability to import power remains limited, especially
in Fairfield County. Individual neighborhoods that were woods and
farms a few years ago are taxing the local distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends Connecticut Light &AMP; Power Co. speed up its
responses to transformer problems and study whether the
distribution system is big enough to handle growing residential
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to build an 600-megawatt capacity electric line under Long
Island Sound from New Haven to Long Island are in the works, but
the project has just received state approval.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's energy demand has changed along with its shift
from a manufacturing economy to a service economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, factories used 37 percent of the state's power,
and commercial use was 29 percent. Today, 40 percent of the power
is for commercial use, which means more air conditioning and longer
evening hours than manufacturing used, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The DPUC wants electric utilities to beef up conservation
measures, particularly for energy-saving air conditioners. The
agency also wants air conditioner installers to notify power
companies when they put in new central air systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
