<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder rate up slightly; perception even bigger problem  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The year 2000 began on an ominous note: The
city's murder rate rose 12 percent in the first three months.
</P>
<P>
   Police brass started wondering whether the plunging homicide
rates of the 1990s were a trend of the past. Then, on paper at
least, things began to improve. For the first half of this year,
murders rose only 2.4 percent, and other violent crimes decreased,
according to statistics released this week.
</P>
<P>
   Perception is a different matter. The still-fresh recollection
of the Central Park attacks has residents and tourists alike
questioning how safe they really are.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to run in the park almost everyday, but I've been going
to the gym more since those attacks,'' said Jenna McLaughlin, 31,
of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 teen-age girls and women were drenched with water,
molested, stripped or robbed by a roving mob in the park on June
11, the day of the city's Puerto Rican Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got lulled into this real sense of security, then the
attacks occurred and made me rethink how safe the city is,''
McLaughlin said. ''I still think it's safe, but I think there's
more crime these days than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tourists, like Masanobu and Yuko Kawabata of Tokyo, are
sticking to Central Park West, admiring the stately apartment
buildings but not venturing into the park.
</P>
<P>
   ''We read about the attacks in the park before we came here, and
decided not to go in,'' Masanobu Kawabata said. ''That was very
scary for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime experts recommend caution, but not panic.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although murders have been down, 1950 is the 20th century's
low point for murders, and we're still nowhere near that,'' noted
Eric Monkkonen, a University of California at Los Angeles professor
who studies urban murders and is writing a history book called
''Murder in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 294 murders among New York's 7.9 million people in
1950, compared to the city's all-time high of 2,290 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The past two years, however, have seen numbers lower than they
have been since the 1960s - a total of 667 homicides last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year the 2.4 percent rise over the same period in 1999 is
an increase of only eight murders - 333 compared with 325 - in a
city of about 7.4 million people. And overall violent crime -
murder, rape, robbery, felony assault, burglary, grand larceny and
auto theft - is down 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Crime experts have attributed the decrease to the aging of baby
boomers, a keener sense of community, good citizenship and the
decreasing use of crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   This year's early concern about the murder rate stemmed in part
from a spate of livery cab driver murders, and two fatal police
shootings. Then things quieted down until just before Memorial Day,
when five Wendy's employees were killed during a robbery in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides have increased greatly in two of the city's five
boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Usually quiet Staten Island had 14 murders through June 25,
compared with five during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx also suffered an increase. After seeing murders drop
in 1999 by 17 percent, the rate through June 25 of this year is up
56.2 percent. Police say 100 people were slain in the Bronx during
the first half of 2000, compared to 64 during the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir started an initiative on March
17 to put more uniformed cops on Bronx streets, concentrating on
violence-prone areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 1653 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0112 </DOCNO>
