<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-NJ--OpSail 2000-NJ-Glance Patience-testing traffic delays expected at Liberty State Park </HEADLINE>
By DERRICK HENRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. - Liberty State Park, with its panoramic view of
New York Harbor, will be a prime location for viewing the parade of
tall ships that will sail into New York Harbor for America's
birthday bash on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But crowds expected to watch the ships from the park likely will
generate traffic delays that will test motorists' patience. State
police are forecasting traffic delays of two to four hours.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 tall ships and classic sailing vessels are
expected to ply the waves into the harbor for OpSail 2000.
Organizers have said they expect a July 4 crowd of 4 million people
along the New York and New Jersey waterfronts. At Liberty State
Park, about 260,000 people are expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Expect to be there for a long period of time,'' state police
Superintendent Col. Carson J. Dunbar Jr. said, referring to the
delays.
</P>
<P>
   State police said New Jersey Turnpike exits 14B and 14C, which
serve the park, will be closed to passenger vehicles on the Fourth
of July. Only shuttle buses and other support vehicles will be
allowed on the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Turnpike officials said they were prepared to close the Newark
Bay/Hudson County Extension if traffic becomes bad enough.
</P>
<P>
   No passenger vehicles will be allowed into the park from 10 p.m.
July 3 to 6 a.m. July 5, state police said. That means visitors on
Tuesday will have to walk into the park, use shuttle buses or NJ
Transit's Light Rail Service to the Liberty State Park Station,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Parking for shuttles will be at the North Bergen Park &AMP; Ride
lots near routes 495 and 3. Parking also has been set aside at the
Vince Lombardi Park &AMP; Ride on the New Jersey Turnpike near
Interchange 18, and at the Military Ocean Terminal in Bayonne off
Route 169. Parking at the park and ride lots will be free,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NJ Transit is scheduled to provide shuttle service to the park
from the ocean terminal lot. Private carriers are scheduled to
provide shuttle service from the North Bergen and Vince Lombardi
lots.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson-Bergen Light Rail will provide service from Bayonne
and Jersey City to the Liberty State Park Station, located about a
mile from the park.
</P>
<P>
   OpSail, which is expected to bring boats from 60 nations, is
combined with the International Naval Review, a flotilla of 40
modern warships from 23 navies.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Sail was established by President John F. Kennedy in
1961 to promote international relations and cultural exchange.
There have been only four other OpSail events: the 1964 New York
World's Fair, the U.S. Bicentennial in 1976, the Statue of Liberty
centennial in 1986 and the Christopher Columbus Quincentennial in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Ships from the OpSail flotilla last week made a stop in the
Delaware River along the New Jersey and Philadelphia waterfronts.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey for the first time will be represented by a ship in
OpSail. The A.J. Meerwald is a restored, 71 year-old Delaware bay
schooner. The former oyster dredge these days is a floating ecology
and maritime history classroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 1715 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
