<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall approves Medicaid contract extension despite doubts  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - State Comptroller H. Carl McCall Friday
approved a two-year contract extension between the state and
Maximus Inc. despite his ''serious concerns'' about the company's
Medicaid managed care enrollment work.
</P>
<P>
   The $43 million contract amendments call for Maximus to continue
handling Medicaid managed care enrollments for the state Health
Department in New York City, and to extend the program to Nassau
and Suffolk counties on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The state's current contract with Maximus was to expire at
midnight Friday. It was signed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said his review of the contract extension raised
questions in his mind of how accurate the information was which the
company was providing to Medicaid recipients. Those same concerns
were raised in 1999 by Mark Green, New York City's public advocate.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said he was also troubled that as of earlier this month,
information about Medicaid managed care was not available from
Maximus in languages other than English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Health Care Financing Administration also raised
questions about the Maximus contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 670,000 people currently enrolled in Medicaid
managed care in New York state, about 390,000 in New York City.
State Health Commissioner Dr. Antonia Novello says she wants to
expand enrollments to 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau and Suffolk county enrollments are currently handled by
local social services officials.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus is not providing health care coverage or services in New
York, but is finding eligible Medicaid recipients and enrolling
them in managed care.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department is confident Maximus can do the job its
contract calls for and has been pleased with the responsiveness of
the company when problems or concerns have been pointed out,
department spokesman John Signor said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to monitor and oversee Maximus operations as
we always have to ensure a Medicaid recipient receives quality
health care in managed care,'' Signor said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman added that Health Department officials were
''amazed'' that McCall continues to raise concerns about Maximus
since the department believes it answered them months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are really old issues,'' Signor said. ''They have mostly
been taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCall spokeswoman Theresa Bourgeois said the comptroller's
office has been frustrated that although many of the problems with
Maximus have long been identified, the Health Department has not
guaranteed they would be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know the problems aren't new,'' she said. ''The problem is
they've failed to address them. But they have now agreed to address
the issues, which is why the comptroller agreed to let the contract
to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Maximus, based in McLean, Va., is currently embroiled in a court
battle in New York City over the awarding of more than $100 million
in city welfare-to-work contracts to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus is the nation's largest operator of welfare-to-work
programs for state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the company Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
