<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 more dead birds in Bergen County test positive for West Nile virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - Three dead crows found this week in
Bergen County were infected with the West Nile virus, the county
said Friday, bringing to four the number of crows found carrying
the disease, which can kill humans.
</P>
<P>
   Humans get the virus from mosquitoes that have bitten infected
birds. Seven people died last year in New York, when the West Nile
strain of encephalitis first surfaced in the region, sickening
dozens.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a cause for concern, but not a cause for alarm,''
Bergen County executive William P. ''Pat'' Schuber said.
</P>
<P>
   He said no infected mosquitoes have been found in Bergen County,
which has the largest population of the state's 21 counties and is
next to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The crows were found on Sunday and Monday. The Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention on Friday confirmed that the birds
had the West Nile strain, Schuber said.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County dispatched crews Friday to the neighborhoods where
the birds were found.
</P>
<P>
   One crew will use hand-held sprayers to apply larvaecide and
will treat catch basins in the area with larvaecide briquettes to
kill developing mosquitoes, Schuber said. Before that, another crew
will take larvae samples.
</P>
<P>
   There is no need yet to apply insecticide to kill adult
mosquitoes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the dead crows were found in Westwood, while the third
was in River Edge, where a virus-infected crow was found in early
June.
</P>
<P>
   Blood tests of the county's ''sentinel'' chickens have not found
signs of the virus, said Mark Guarino, director of the county
health department.
</P>
<P>
   Those caged birds are considered the most reliable indicator of
the presence of the virus. Unlike the crows, they cannot move from
place to place, so if they test positive for the virus, authorities
would know definitively that West Nile is present in Bergen County.
Other cages of sentinel chickens are located elsewhere in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the virus is here, it is here in a very limited way and has
not shown up in any surveillance yet,'' Guarino said.
</P>
<P>
   The county health department is monitoring hospitals and
clinics, but has not found the disease in any people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Rockland County, N.Y., two dead crows have been found
to be infected with the West Nile virus this year.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 112 blood samples from sentinel chickens in all 21 New
Jersey counties have found no evidence of West Nile, said Dennis
McGowan, a spokesman for the state Department of Health and Senior
Services.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 170 mosquito pools from around the state have all
tested negative.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 191 dead crows and three dead pigeons from all counties
except Camden and Cape May, West Nile has only been found in the
four Bergen County crows, McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County has no plans for aerial spraying in residential
areas, which Schuber has said could cause more of a health risk
than it prevents. It uses helicopters to spray pesticides in marshy
areas that are not near neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The county has introduced fish that feed on mosquito larvae into
ponds and waterways, and is urging people to eliminate breeding
grounds for the mosquitoes by preventing standing water from
accumulating on their property.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Health Department:
http://www.state.nj.us/health
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County West Nile Virus-related mosquito treatment info:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.njcommunity.com/sites/bcdhslincs
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 1723 </TRAILER>
