<HEADLINE> Spending Bill Blocks Water Rules  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation that received final congressional
approval Friday would block federal regulators from moving forward
with a program to curb runoff from farms and businesses that
pollutes the nation's waterways.
</P>
<P>
   A provision in an $11 billion emergency spending bill that
passed the Senate Friday would prevent the Environmental Protection
Agency from implementing the program before October 2001, the start
of the government's 2002 budget year. President Clinton is expected
to sign the legislation, which provides money for the Pentagon,
drug fighting in Colombia and other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ''EPA regards this as another anti-environmental assault by the
congressional leadership against the administration's efforts to
bring cleaner, healthier water to all Americans,'' agency spokesman
Dave Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA provision was put in the bill ''late in the game without
warning,'' said Linda Ricci, a spokeswoman for the White House
budget office. She said the administration prevented lawmakers from
attaching several other provisions that it also considered bad for
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Under EPA's proposed program, states would be given 15 years
develop plans for cleaning up every waterway that fails to meet
water quality standards. EPA estimates more than 20,000 streams and
lakes don't meet water-quality standards, or about 40 percent of
the nation's lakes, rivers and streams.
</P>
<P>
   Landowners would be required to get pollution-discharge permits
if the EPA found they were contributing to nearby water quality
problems and if a state had failed to draft an adequate plan for
improving water quality.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials said they had intended to implement the program
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits have imposed deadlines on some states to develop the
cleanup plans for rivers and streams. Only 1,300 of the estimated
40,000 needed plans had been approved by EPA as of last year, the
General Accounting Office said.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials say it would be up to each state to decide what
landowners would have to do to control pollutants, and logging
operations have been dropped from the program. The proposal still
has faced strong criticism from farm-state lawmakers of both
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is overwhelming opposition across the country to the
EPA's proposals,'' said Rep. Larry Combest, R-Texas, chairman of
the House Agriculture Committee. ''The sheer fact that independent
scientists, farmers, foresters and environmentalists have all urged
withdrawal of these rules should give the EPA pause.''
</P>
<P>
   An Agriculture Department official told Combest's committee this
week that the EPA program was so unpopular with farm interests that
it had become the ''new four-letter word in rural America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1727 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
