<HEADLINE> Documents Show U.S. Filmmaker Shot  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An informant told the U.S. Embassy in Chile in
1987 that an American filmmaker killed in the tumultuous aftermath
of a 1973 military coup was shot by Chilean soldiers because he was
judged to be a ''foreign extremist,'' according to government
documents made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the information was not disclosed, and the
documents indicated the embassy was unable to determine whether the
information was credible.
</P>
<P>
   The American was Charles Horman, whose murder in the
blood-filled post-coup period was the subject of a 1982 movie,
''Missing.'' The information received by the embassy about the case
was contained in a release of 505 previously classified documents,
most from State Department files.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Horman, the documents contain information about
the murder of American journalist Frank Teruggi, also in September
1973; and Boris Weisfeiler, a Russian emigre and mathematics
professor who disappeared in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Attending a news conference at which the files were released,
Joyce Horman, Charles Horman's widow, said she was disappointed
that the mystery about her husband's death remains.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not found the answer,'' she said. ''Our quest is not
over.''
</P>
<P>
   The embassy was told, the documents said, that Horman was
arrested at his home in Santiago on Sept. 18, 1973, one week after
President Salvador Allende was deposed in the coup by Gen. Augusto
Pinochet. Allende was killed in the coup.
</P>
<P>
   The Chilean source's first contact with the embassy occurred in
February 1987, more than 13 years after Horman's death. He told the
embassy that Horman was taken to the National Stadium after
interrogation the day after his arrest and was shot the following
evening.
</P>
<P>
   An April 27, 1987, memo from the embassy in Santiago to the
State Department reported that the home where Horman was staying
was reputed to be housing ''extremists,'' and documents found there
confirmed this suspicion, the informant said.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy memo continues, ''According to (name blacked out),
the authorities at the stadium did not know that Horman was an
American since his paperwork arrived after his death, and his poor
knowledge of Spanish made it difficult for him to understand and
answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''They only know that he was a foreigner and an 'extremist.' The
body was taken from the stadium and left at a location to create
the idea that he had been killed in a firefight with the
military.''
</P>
<P>
   The embassy also was told that Brig. Pedro Espinoza, a top
commander in Pinochet's security service, approved Horman's
killing. A Chilean tribunal convicted Espinoza in 1994 in the death
of Orlando Letelier, killed on a Washington street in 1976 by a
bomb placed by Chilean agents.
</P>
<P>
   Several pages of the documents address whether the embassy
source was providing legitimate information.
</P>
<P>
   A May 1987 memo to the embassy from then-Undersecretary of State
Michael Armacost said: ''We have serious doubts about (name blacked
out) credibility. ... He could be a government of Chile plant
intended to entrap embassy personnel, a sophisticated visa-shopper
or absolutely legitimate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 1810 </TRAILER>
