<HEADLINE> Trenton man makes People's eligible bachelor list  </HEADLINE>
By J.J. THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON (AP) - Jeff Eppenstine is one hot package that delivers
- guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   People Magazine named the UPS deliveryman from Chambersburg one
of America's 100 most eligible bachelors. In the edition that hit
newsstands Friday, his photo appears along with Hollywood hunks
George Clooney, Ben Affleck and Freddie Prinze Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Eppenstine, 31, heard about the contest through friends of a
co-worker, but never expected to make the final cut. He and his
relatives were ''flipping out'' when they saw his photo and short
write-up in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was cracking up,'' he said Friday. ''There were all these
guys - celebrities - and they were showing me (with them).''
</P>
<P>
   He's already been mentioned on ''Entertainment Tonight,''
''Dateline'' and ''Live with Regis and Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Morrisville (Pa.) High School graduate spent most of his
Friday morning at the New Jersey shore handling calls from the
media.
</P>
<P>
   ''My friends can't believe it because the phone keeps ringing,''
he said. ''I never thought it would happen to me. I might as well
enjoy it while I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the attention, Eppenstine said he's not fighting off
single women. Although People Magazine posted an e-mail address for
anyone interested in contacting him, he's only had one response so
far.
</P>
<P>
   ''It said something like, 'You're too hot for words. Love,
Mom.'''
</P>
<P>
   UPS, meanwhile, doesn't mind the attention its employee is
getting. The company is excited for him, said Laurie Valle,
communications supervisor, but she contends most of its employees
look pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a lot of workers at UPS are always (out and) about and
it keeps them in shape,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eppenstine said he spends free time during the week working on
his house. He also goes to Philadelphia night clubs and works as a
bartender at Bob's Woodside Pub in Robbinsville.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine located the bachelors through a four-month search,
with employees talking to their friends and family members,
according to People's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Eppenstine said he learned of the search through a coworker's
future sister-in-law, who knows a People editor. He was interviewed
several times and was scheduled for a two-hour photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   When the magazine called for follow-up interviews, he was warned
not to get his hopes up. Eppenstine found out about a week ago that
he had made the list when someone called to check his name for a
photo caption.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy began a few days later, but Eppenstine said he's not
letting it go to his head.
</P>
<P>
   ''On Monday I'll still be back at work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
