<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> If weather cooperates, July Fourth holiday could be 4-day event  </HEADLINE>
By NINA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - With sunny skies predicted through Monday
for the entire state, some transportation officials in New Jersey
think the July Fourth holiday weekend will turn into a four-day
fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ingoglia, a spokesman for the Garden State Parkway, said
his agency predicted 4.7 million vehicles will travel the parkway
between Friday and Tuesday. That's about 100,000 more cars than the
last July Fourth weekend. Some 1.5 million vehicles travel the
parkway on an average work day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Turnpike officials are predicting 3.3 million cars
will travel its 148-mile stretch between Friday and Wednesday.
Their figures assume vacationers will go back to work on Monday,
head out again on Tuesday and return home on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's going to happen on Monday is questionable,'' said
Vincent L. Leonetti, deputy executive director of the South Jersey
Transportation Authority, which runs the Atlantic City Expressway.
Will visitors who spend the holiday at the Jersey Shore return to
work on Monday and come back on Tuesday?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy travel is expected despite higher gasoline prices this
year. Regular unleaded gasoline averages $1.57 in New Jersey. That
means a typical two-car family faces an increase of about $600 in
their annual fuel expenditures over last year's prices, the
American Automobile Association said.
</P>
<P>
   About 32 million Americans are expected to use their cars on the
Fourth of July weekend, the AAA said. The organization also said
that number is nearly 4 percent higher than last year and the
greatest one-year jump for the holiday since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ingoglia said the July Fourth weekend is very dependent on the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it rains, people will go to a movie or move their barbecue
inside instead of going to the shore.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service predicted possible thunderstorms on
Tuesday for every part of the state except the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the weather, there will be plenty to do, no matter
when the holiday weekend begins or ends.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic City area is ''going to be a jamming place,'' said
Susan Ricciardi of the Atlantic City Convention &AMP; Visitors
Authority. ''The Boardwalk and the beach are a natural attraction
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Northern New Jersey will have attractions for those who don't
want to fight the shore traffic.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 tall ships and classic sailing vessels are
expected to glide into the New York Harbor for OpSail 2000.
Organizers have said they expect a July Fourth crowd of four
million people along the New York and New Jersey waterfronts. At
Liberty State Park, about 260,000 people are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Some of New Jersey's largest concert halls have sold out shows
for the extended weekend. PNC Bank Arts Center in Holmdel is
hosting the classic rock 'n roll group The Who on Saturday and teen
pop sensation Britney Spears on Sunday and Monday at its
17,000-seat open-air facility.
</P>
<P>
   The E-Centre in Camden will supply the alternative sound of
Phish on Monday and Tuesday and Spears on Wednesday at its
25,000-seat arena.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Springfield will perform Saturday at the Meadowlands Fair,
held in the Giants Stadium parking lot through July 9.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Al Della Fave, spokesman for the New Jersey State Police,
said troopers will be in full force over the holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be high visibility to get people to think twice''
before they get behind the wheel, said Della Fave. Eight people
died over the last July Fourth weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Della Fave added that troopers will be on the lookout for
fireworks. Possession of fireworks - Roman candles, M-80s, cherry
bombs and even sparklers - carry a maximum penalty of a $1,000 fine
and 30 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers confiscate between six and eight tons of illegal
explosives each year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Police marine bureau will also be patrolling the
waters, looking for those who are driving aggressively or under the
influence of drugs or alcohol. In New Jersey, boaters must be at
least 16 and have a boating safety certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from New Jersey power utilities said they are not
predicting any problems during the holiday weekend. Mild
temperatures and low humidity are expected to keep demand down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're actually anticipating low demand over the weekend
because the weather won't be (extreme) at all,'' said Kathleen
Ellis, a spokeswoman for PSE&AMP;G, the state's largest utility.
</P>
<P>
   Customers probably won't have the same problems this summer as
they did last July Fourth weekend, when blackouts occurred
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said most of the problems were caused by the distribution
system. While the utility's system performed well last year, she
said PSE&AMP;G made major investments in the areas where it was the
weakest.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does that mean nothing will happen? Of course we can't say
that,'' Ellis said. ''But we are anticipating an eventless
summer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
