<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gazprom Names Kremlin Aide Chairman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Shareholders in Russia's natural gas monopoly
Gazprom named a top Kremlin official Friday to head its board of
directors, a move that could herald tighter government control over
the country's largest company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also unexpectedly elected two shareholder rights
advocates to the company's board in what many observers considered
a sign of improved corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom is the top source of revenues for the federal budget.
Europe depends on the Russian company for more than a quarter of
its gas.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitry Medvedev, deputy head of the Kremlin administration who
is considered to have close ties to President Vladimir Putin,
replaced Viktor Chernomyrdin as chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who founded Gazprom 11 years ago, was Boris
Yeltsin's longest-serving prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev gave few signs about his priorities, saying only that
he would ''fulfill the laws of the company and protect the
interests of shareholders, first and foremost the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder rights advocates are Burckhard Bergmann, deputy
head of Germany's Ruhrgas and the first foreigner on the board, and
Boris Fyodorov, a former finance minister and current parliamentary
deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhrgas owns 4 percent of Gazprom. Fyodorov is considered a
strong defender of the rights of minority shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Following the appointments, Gazprom shares jumped 10 percent to
25.5 cents on the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom continues to face financial pressures as a result of
declining output and difficulty in collecting payments from
deadbeat customers.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Rem Vyakhirev said 80 percent of the company's
gas comes from fields with declining productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The government, owner of a controlling 38.37 percent stake, won
four seats in addition to Medvedev's: Economics and Trade Minister
German Gref, State Property Minister Farit Gazizullin, Deputy Prime
Minister Viktor Khristenko, and Antimonopoly Policies &AMP; Enterprise
Support Minister Ilya Uzhanov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
