<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton raises $5.1 million; Lazio $4.5 million  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton's Republican rival
for the U.S. Senate, Rick Lazio, has been raising money at a much
faster rate than the first lady for the six weeks he's been in the
race, figures released Friday showed.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman from Long Island has collected more than $4.5
million since entering the race on May 20, his campaign aides said.
Lazio had earlier raised $3.5 million for a possible Senate run
before suspending that effort last year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton aides said Friday that she had raised $5.1
million over the past three months, boosting her total collections
to almost $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very excited,'' Lazio campaign spokesman Dan McLagan
said as he reported the new numbers. ''We had only half a quarter
to raise this money.''
</P>
<P>
   In the all important bottom line of cash in hand, how much each
campaign has available to spend immediately, Lazio reported $5.4
million and Clinton, $6.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio fund raising over six weeks works out to $750,000 a
week compared with $425,000 a week for the first lady over the 12
weeks she was at work over the second quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson questioned the rate of
fund raising comparison, saying some of Lazio's $4.5 million
certainly came from before May 20 because the congressman had to
have been raising money for an expected House re-election race.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a very, very small percentage,'' McLagan said. The
Lazio spokesman said he did not have such figures available Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not a bad start, but he's going to have to do a lot
better,'' said Hank Sheinkopf, a veteran New York Democratic
strategist, when told about Lazio's effort.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said he will need $15 million or more for the race,
although some of his top advisers think he may need twice that
amount to beat the better-known first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton financial advisers have said they expect to raise at
least $25 million for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides sought to portray themselves as the underdog in the
money chase.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign manager Bill de Blasio said, ''Rick Lazio and
the national Republican fund-raising machine will outraise us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign manager Bill Dal Col said, ''We know we will be
outspent ... but we will have enough to wage our underdog effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio entered the race when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani withdrew from
the contest after being diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the Senate race, Giuliani had raised more than
$19 million through the end of March. He is refunding about $2.8
million of that to donors, along with letters urging them to send
the money to Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's former campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, said
Friday that between the end of March and May 19 when the mayor quit
the race, his campaign had collected additional donations of more
than $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum said there has been no decision made yet on what to
do with Senate campaign money not refunded to donors. Both state
and national Republican campaign committees are hoping to get at
least a large share of whatever money the New York City mayor has
left.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had been preparing for a possible Senate run last year
until Gov. George Pataki asked him to bow out in favor of Giuliani.
At that point, Lazio had already raised about $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign figures being trumpeted Friday cover April, May and
June. The candidates' reports, providing details of that fund
raising that the campaigns did not provide Friday, are supposed to
be filed with the Federal Election Commission by July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began raising money for the Senate race one year ago.
She collected more than $8 million last year and $4.7 million in
the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an extremely strong filing, and we are very pleased,''
de Blasio said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While the campaigns were tallying up their donations, Sen. John
McCain attacked the Democrats for launching a new round of
television ads criticizing Lazio's congressional record. The ads
were paid for by ''soft money'' donations to the federal Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted that he and Lazio voted this week for legislation
sent to President Clinton that would require public disclosure of
donors to some political committees that have previously been able
to keep their donor lists secret.
</P>
<P>
   ''So what were Hillary Clinton and the Democratic Party doing
while Rick Lazio was helping lead the fight for reform?'' McCain
asked in a statement. ''They were announcing a $400,000 soft-money
ad campaign paid for by special interest money to attack Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton: http://www.hillary2000.org.
</P>
<P>
   For Lazio: http://www.lazio.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 1851 </TRAILER>
