<HEADLINE> Journalists: Fox Campaign Hostile  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Journalists covering Mexico's top opposition
candidate accuse the campaign's media team of hostility, including
pressuring a radio network to reassign one reporter and physically
threatening another.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the journalists' compaints revolve areound Martha
Sahagun, the media coordinator for Vicente Fox's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters say Sahagun has made calls to editors to ask that
reporters be reassigned, and has threatened to withdraw advertising
unless they heeded her.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists who made the accusations to The Associated Press
included Georgina Morett of the newspaper Milenio, Fabiola Sanchez
of CNI television news, and Maria Eugenia Rojas of Radio Formula --
who was pulled from covering the campaign after an argument with
Sahagun. Several other reporters spoke to The AP on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters say many of the problems are a result of the
inexperience of Fox's media team in a country where a single party
has held the presidency for 71 years, and where the news media
often have been used as a tool to discredit the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of ruling-party candidate Francisco Labastida,
Fox's main rival, also has been accused of trying to influence the
news media, and some journalists said they were ordered by editors
to give biased coverage in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fox campaign, the discontent extends to a majority of
reporters following him, who say the campaign is routinely hostile
and unhelpful -- and at times has clearly crossed the line.
</P>
<P>
   In the most severe case, a reporter working for a newspaper with
a clear anti-Fox editorial line was threatened by two of the
candidate's bodyguards, according to other journalists who
witnessed the incidents and spoke only on condition of anonymity
for fear of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Sahagun wouldn't directly confirm the threat, but said: ''I must
accept that there have been some incidents about which we have
talked with the affected parties and have issued an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox apparently didn't know about the apology. He told The
Associated Press that he knew of no tensions with the news media,
adding: ''We respect the freedom of the press in an absolute
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas was pulled off covering the campaign by Rogerio Azcarraga,
the owner of the radio network where she worked. Rojas said she was
taken off the story on May 24, right after she had a fight with
Sahagun.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president of operations for the radio network, Gabriel
Nunez, conceded that ''in response to a plea from the campaign
team, we sent another person.'' Sahagun refused to discuss the
matter, saying only that it had been resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
