<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High court suppresses confession, orders new trial in 1991 murder  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Supreme Court ruled Friday that
the confession of a suspect in a 1991 North Brunswick rape and
murder should have been thrown out because he was illegally
arrested and interrogated for nine hours.
</P>
<P>
   New information about the case unearthed by police midway
through the interrogation was not enough to justify the tainted
confession that followed, the justices ruled in the unanimous
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Richard J. Chippero deserves to be retried, said the
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Chippero, of North Brunswick, was convicted of the July 23, 1991
rape and murder of his neighbor, Ermina Ross Tocci.
</P>
<P>
   Police interviewed the then-24-year-old after he was identified
by another neighbor as being in the vicinity of Tocci's mobile home
the day of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   During a five-week trial, an expert told the jury that Chippero
''underwent significant psychological alterations'' during the nine
hours he was held by police, and blanked out near the end. The
defendant has no recall of his taped confession, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the jury chose not to sentence Chippero to death, he
was sentenced to two life terms.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed his conviction, claiming he was arrested without
probable cause then fabricated his confession to appease
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division upheld the conviction and admissibility
of the confession, finding no flagrant police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court reversed the appeals court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''The eleventh-hour discovery by police officers of allegedly
new information ... is a weak reed on which to rest the state's
claim of intervening circumstances,'' the court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Frank J. Pugliese said Friday that his client,
who is serving time at New Jersey State Prison in Trenton, was
''choked up'' when told the news.
</P>
<P>
   ''He cried a bit, but they were happy tears,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Middlesex County Prosecutor's Office chooses to retry him
without the benefit of the tainted confession, Chippero is
confident of acquittal, Pugliese said.
</P>
<P>
   Two telephone calls placed to the prosecutor's office by The
Associated Press on Friday were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant state Attorney General Anne Pascow said she was
disappointed in the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought the Appellate decision was fair,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices found fault with the appeals court ruling that the
length of time between the suspect's arrest and his confession
somehow diminished the illegal nature of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ''a contrary rule would encourage police officers who
arrest without probable cause to conduct lengthy interrogations in
an effort to purge the unlawful arrest of its unconstitutional
taint,'' they wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
