<HEADLINE> Lebanon Court Convicts 8  </HEADLINE>
Headlines Headlines Headlines .....   
Lebanon court sends alleged bin Laden followers to jail
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Eight alleged followers of America's
most-wanted terror suspect, Osama bin Laden, were convicted Friday
on charges that included planning terrorist attacks. They were
sentenced to prison terms ranging from two weeks to five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese military court acquitted three suspects and
sentenced two more in absentia, one to 15 years and another to one
year.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects were accused of conspiring to carry out terrorist
acts and possessing weapons and detonators with the intent to use
them. Charges also included involvement in circulating counterfeit
money and forging passports.
</P>
<P>
   The trial began June 16 and all the suspects who appeared in
court pleaded innocence. The Military Tribunal, whose rulings
cannot be appealed, issued the sentences after four hours of
deliberations Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight who received prison terms, two were sentenced to
five years in prison. One woman received nine months, a man got six
months, three people received one month prison terms and one person
was sentenced to two weeks in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The trial in Beirut coincided with one of 28 terror suspects in
Jordan who are alleged to belong to a group associated with bin
Laden. They are charged with planning to attack U.S. and Israeli
tourists during New Year's celebrations in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, a Saudi-born millionaire, is wanted for the 1998
bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. The bombings
killed 224 people. Bin Laden is thought to be in hiding in
Afghanistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
