<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Offers Regional Compromise  </HEADLINE>
By ANGELA CHARLTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin won new
parliamentary victories Friday in his bid to strengthen control
over independent-minded regions, but hinted he'd be willing to
soften the plan to appease angry provincial bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has said reining in unruly provinces is necessary to mend
the economy and prevent Russia from breaking up, and has devised a
three-point proposal on how to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of parliament, or State Duma, passed one of the
provisions Friday: a bill that would allow Putin to remove elected
governors who were found to have violated federal law. The bill,
passed in a final reading 399-9 with three abstentions, also would
allow him to suspend governors who face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma later gave tentative approval to a second bill, which
would allow Putin to fire city mayors who violate federal law.
Lawmakers removed part of the bill that would have allowed
governors to dismiss the mayors, leaving that right only to Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The third part of Putin's plan, passed by the Duma earlier this
month, would revamp the upper house of parliament, or Federation
Council, by removing the governors and heads of local legislatures
from the body and replacing them with appointed legislators. The
bill also would remove regional leaders' immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the governors and regional leaders in the upper
house rejected that bill this week, saying it would give the
president too much power.
</P>
<P>
   All three bills must also be approved by the upper house, unless
the lower house can garner a two-thirds majority of 300 votes to
override an upper-house veto.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin was apparently concerned that confrontation with the
governors could erode his support in the provinces. The strong
criticism of the plan by the governors highlighted cracks in the
widespread backing he has enjoyed since his election in March.
</P>
<P>
   Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov told reporters Friday that Putin
met with him and proposed setting up a committee to work out a
compromise version of the bill on ousting the governors from the
upper house.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov said that Putin was ready to consider amending the
bill to allow some regional leaders to keep their Federation
Council seats.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Kharitonov, the head of the Agrarian faction, said Putin
told him in a separate meeting Thursday that he was willing to let
regional leaders keep their seats in the upper house until their
current terms expire.
</P>
<P>
   Putin hasn't spoken publicly on the issue, and the Kremlin press
service had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma voted Friday to propose a joint committee to work out a
compromise version, and gave the Federation Council until Wednesday
to agree to take part.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an act of goodwill on our side, and it's up to them
whether to accept it or not. If they reject it, we will override
the (upper house's) veto,'' said Gennady Raikov, the leader of the
pro-Kremlin People's Deputy group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
