<HEADLINE> Whitman cuts $50 million, then signs $21.4 billion budget for new fiscal year </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman on Friday slashed $50
million from the state budget, including a special appropriation
for the one Democratic state senator who voted ''no,'' before
signing the $21.4 billion document into law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill signing came on the final day before the start of the
2000-2001 fiscal year at midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she imposed the vetoes in order to preserve a
surplus in the budget of $870 million, saying lawmakers had tacked
on too much extra spending that dug into the reserve of cash she
maintained is essential to protect the state's financial credit
rating.
</P>
<P>
   The budget includes many of the governor's hallmark initiatives
for the year, including $45 million for a tax break for some
240,000 low-income working families that will give them a
tax-return check next year even though many of them pay no state
income taxes in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The budget provides for the second-phase increase in a school
tax rebate program that will bring homeowners checks averaging $240
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The largest spending items include $6.7 billion for school aid,
$2.8 billion of it for the so-called ''special needs'' school
districts, mainly urban, poor systems as designated in state
Supreme Court decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The $21.4 billion budget is up 10 percent from the $19.5 billion
budget signed into law one year ago, and up 40 percent from the
$15.3 billion budget Whitman signed in her first year in office in
1994. Over those seven years the overall cost-of-living increased
about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the outgoing budget for the 1999-2000 fiscal year
that came to an end at midnight Friday was finalized at $20.1
billion, including a last-minute, $208 million appropriation
approved by the Legislature on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This means the budget signed last June had about $600 million
more pumped into it in supplemental spending proposed by the
Whitman administration and approved by the GOP-controlled
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   If that pattern of past years holds true over the next 12 months
- the last full fiscal year of Whitman's term - the state's budget
will clear $22 billion for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   This extra appropriation on Thursday caused some confusion among
lawmakers who believed they were sending the governor budget
legislation with an $870 million surplus when in fact the
Treasurer's office said it was only $825 million, prompting the
governor's heavy cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in overall spending was cited by the five members
of the Senate and Assembly who opposed the budget on Thursday when
it was up for final votes in the Legislature. It passed 38-1 in the
Senate and 75-4 in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   One of those opponents, Sen. John Lynch, D-Middlesex, paid for
his ''no'' vote. Whitman used her line-item veto to kill three
special appropriations Lynch had requested totaling $300,000 to
help New Brunswick pay for a shuttle bus, street-lighting and a
housing rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, the former Democratic minority leader and the last
Democrat to serve as Senate president, has been a caustic critic of
the governor's budget policies throughout her term, chastising her
Thursday for doing too little in times of plenty to reduce the
state's debts.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman in response Friday was remarkably candid in explaining
she cut the funds in retribution for Lynch's vote. Such political
payback has been common in state budget decisions but is rarely
acknowledged so openly.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't think the budget was good,'' Whitman said. ''He
chose not to support the budget which indicated to me that he
didn't think that those projects were all that important. ... He
voted against his own additions.''
</P>
<P>
   With regard to her overall cuts, Whitman said many of the
lawmakers' local pet projects had to be deleted because they might
set a bad precedent.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, asked about her cut of $120,000 to help Burlington
Township buy new police cars, Whitman said other state agencies had
funding for such purchases and the door would be opened for towns
everywhere to seek this kind of special aid.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very difficult in flush times to say no,'' Whitman said.
''The precedent that would be set would put a huge strain on next
year and the year after and the year after that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 1932 </TRAILER>
