<HEADLINE> Egypt Gives US $5M in Crash Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Egypt gave the United States $5 million Friday
to help pay for the search and rescue efforts that followed last
year's EgyptAir crash, a congressman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very pleased to receive the $5 million payment and look
forward to soon receiving the balance,'' Rep. John Duncan Jr.,
R-Tenn., chairman of the House Transportation aviation
subcommittee, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's total bill was $10.6 million, which means that country
still owe about $5.6 million, Duncan spokesman David Balloff said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They would like to see more details, which would be a
breakdown of the 10.6 million,'' Balloff said.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Ambassador Nahil Fahmy had said in a recent letter to
Congress that Egypt would pay ''$5 million immediately and the
remaining amount ... expeditiously'' to help with the costs of the
U.S.-led investigation of the October crash into the ocean off the
Massachusetts island of Nantucket. All 217 people aboard the plane
were killed, including 101 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's payment became a more urgent issue in Congress because
the investigating agency -- the National Transportation Safety Board
-- has already spent much of its budget for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB expects the bill for the search and rescue and
investigation that followed the crash to top $20 million, Balloff
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has not reported a cause in the crash. Some aviation
experts have raised the possibility that a co-pilot deliberately
crashed the plane, an idea Egyptian authorities have denied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
