<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proposal could Be Boon for Ethanol  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The corn-based fuel additive ethanol would be
easier and perhaps cheaper to use as an octane-booster in gasoline
under a government proposal announced Friday that has been long
sought by farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the Environmental Protection Agency has required
that gasoline sold in cities with the most severe summer smog
contain oxygenates to make it burn cleaner. The most popular
octane-booster is MTBE, but ethanol is the oxygenate of choice in
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   However, the program's pollution-reduction goals were tightened
this year, and that created problems for the use of ethanol in
so-called reformulated gasoline. Because it evaporates more readily
in summer months, it had to be mixed with a specially tailored
gasoline to burn clean enough to qualify for the program.
</P>
<P>
   The cost and difficulty of producing that new blend has been
blamed by some for soaring gas prices in cities like Chicago and
Milwaukee, where most gasoline sold contains ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   The new EPA proposal would give ethanol credit for reducing
carbon monoxide emissions. That newly recognized environmental
benefit of using the alternative fuel could make special blending
unnecessary, meaning reformulated gasoline containing ethanol would
be less costly to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and Midwestern lawmakers, worried the stricter clean-air
rules would wipe ethanol out of the program, have criticized the
EPA for not moving faster on the proposal. They have been pleading
for action on this issue for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ethanol is highly subsidized by the federal government, and some
states. Those who blend gasoline with ethanol receive a
5.4-cent-a-gallon federal tax break, and the reformulated gasoline
program is the primary market for the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   But some environmentalists dispute ethanol's environmental
credentials, citing for instance the large amounts of pollution
produced in growing and harvesting corn, its main ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will take comment on the proposal for two months, and
expects to issue a final regulation by the end of the year, an EPA
official said.
</P>
<P>
   That process will take far too long to have any impact on high
gas prices in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're really talking about next summer,'' said Monte Shaw,
spokesman for the Renewable Fuels Association, a group that lobbies
on behalf of ethanol producers. ''It won't have any effect this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   And ethanol boosters also were disappointed the EPA did not give
ethanol credit for larger reductions in carbon monoxide emissions.
A request for the new regulation from the Illinois EPA suggested a
credit more than three times bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought the science (for the larger credit) was pretty
sound,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The ethanol industry, led by agribusiness giant Archer Daniels
Midland Co., hopes to significantly increase the fuel's use as MTBE
is phased out because of concerns about it leaking into water
supplies. This rule has been seen as crucial to those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to give incentive to areas that are using MTBE to use
ethanol,'' said Robert Perciasepe, EPA's assistant administrator
for air and radiation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
