<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Perot Won't Run for President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Two-time presidential candidate Ross Perot rejected
supporters' efforts to put his name on the Reform Party's primary ballot Friday,
clearing away a big potential hurdle for Pat Buchanan's bid. Russell Verney,
Perot's spokesman, said the Texas billionaire decided against running in the
primary because he had no intention of actually competing for the White House in
November.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ark. Court Panel Files Vs. Clinton
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- In an unprecedented rebuke of a sitting president,
an Arkansas Supreme Court committee today sued President Clinton to strip him of
his law license. Declaring he lacked ''overall fitness'' to be a lawyer, the
panel accused the president of serious misconduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair,
including false testimony. ''The conduct of Mr. Clinton ... was motivated by a
desire to protect himself from the embarrassment of his own conduct,'' the
court's Committee on Professional Conduct wrote. Clinton has 30 days to respond,
and his private attorney vowed a vigorous fight to retain the law license.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Turns Over E-Mail Tapes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A judge disclosed today that the White House has yet to
recover any missing e-mails sought by investigators and it is turning over
backup tapes that might contain the messages to Independent Counsel Robert Ray
and the Justice Department. The FBI will now step in and try to retrieve the
missing e-mails, two law enforcement officials told The Associated Press.
Congress, Ray and Justice are investigating whether the e-mail problem was an
innocent mistake, as the White House contends, or part of an effort to obstruct
their investigations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't To Limit UC Role at Los Alamos
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a string of security lapses, the Energy Department
gave notice today that it intends to strip the University of California of its
security and some management responsibilities involving nuclear weapons programs
at Los Alamos and another government research lab. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson told the university its contracts for managing the Los Alamos and
Lawrence Livermore labs ''must be restructured ... to make much-needed
improvements to security.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hanford Fire Dying Out
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- The wildfire that raced across nearly half of the
Hanford nuclear complex was all but extinguished Friday, and Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson gave assurances that the flames did not spread radiation. The
190,000-acre blaze, which was ignited by sparks from an auto wreck and exploded
into a 30-mph inferno in less than a day. It burned 45 percent of the
560-square-mile reservation plus 20 homes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congress Passes $11.2B Spending Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress sent President Clinton an $11.2 billion emergency
measure for Colombia, the Pentagon and victims of domestic disasters. The Senate
approved the bill by voice vote today after leaders agreed that in a future bill
they will undo $6.3 billion of accounting gimmicks that the emergency measure
contains. Those gimmicks -- like shifting payments of some veterans' benefits by
a few days so they would be charged against this fiscal year instead of next
year -- were mostly designed to let lawmakers squeeze extra spending into next
year's budget.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FCC To Study Internet Access
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission is looking at
whether old rules designed to break open the local Bell monopolies extend to new
Web services still in their infancy. The FCC's review could have implications
for the long-running debate over whether cable Internet providers must give
other online companies access to their lines. So far, the commission has
declined to impose such a requirement, fearing that any regulation would slow
the growth of the emerging market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 50; Nasdaq Climbs 89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended a difficult first half of 2000 on an upbeat
note today as institutional investors bought the year's big winners and
discarded underperformers. Rallying in the final hour of trading, the Dow Jones
industrial average erased a small loss and finished up 49.85 at 10,447.89 in
heavy trading. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by a narrow margin. The Nasdaq
composite index, lifted by computer chips and semiconducter stocks, rose 88.88
to 3,966.11.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.C. Coach Guthridge Retires
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina coach Bill Guthridge retired today
after three years as Dean Smith's successor. Kansas coach Roy Williams, a former
North Carolina assistant under Smith, will succeed Guthridge, a source close to
the university told The Associated Press. Williams said he has agreed to talk to
North Carolina athletic director Dick Baddour, but it is ''completely false''
that he has accepted the job.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER
</SUBHEAD>
