<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Anthrax Vaccine Dwindles  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- -- The Pentagon's supply of the troubled
anthrax vaccine is dwindling, and the military faces the
possibility of having to slow the pace at which soldiers get
inoculated.
</P>
<P>
   No decision has been made to suspend the program, Rear Adm.
Craig Quigley, a Pentagon spokesman, said Friday. But he said tight
supplies and the need for stringent testing require ''a decision on
the way ahead for the program in the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   As of this week, only about 12 percent of the shots needed to
protect all current Pentagon personnel have been administered,
officials said. Just 455,000 of the 2.4 military U.S. military
employees have received at least one of a required six-shot series
to protect against the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccine from a new plant is expected to be ready for use by the
end of the year, Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, any available vaccine would go first to soldiers
based in Southwest Asia and on the Korean Peninsula, where the risk
of exposure is greatest, Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The program is pressing on and has been for several months,''
he said. About 4,500 soldiers and other employees are receiving
shots each day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax is a disease that typically afflicts animals, especially
sheep and cattle. Dry anthrax spores, which can be put into
weapons, can be fatal to humans when inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon commitment to inoculate all 2.4 million U.S.
military personnel arose from fears that soldiers and others could
be exposed to anthrax attacks by terrorists or hostile forces.
</P>
<P>
   Several House members urged Defense Secretary William Cohen last
month to stop vaccinating military personnel until the Pentagon
finds an improved vaccine, and some soldiers have refused
vaccinations.'
</P>
<P>
   About 700 of those who received shots have filed reports that
they suffered some adverse reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Testing is expected to be completed for a lot of about 200,000
stockpiled doses by mid-July, Quigley said. If it passes, officials
will then have to decide how to administer the vaccine most
effectively. If it fails, they will have to decide how best to use
limited supplies until another lot can make it through the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a vaccine-tight environment,'' Quigley said. ''The
potential is there for the need to restructure the program in the
next couple of weeks, but we're certainly not there today.'' He
said safety of the vaccine will be the top priority in any
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Each lot of vaccine undergoes supplemental testing to make sure
it is safe, sterile and potent, Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, several anthrax lots failed to meet potency
requirements specified by the Food and Drug Administration. Some
lots have included fewer than 20,000 shots. The lot now being
tested is one of the biggest, Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting to the point on testing where ... we have to be
careful as to how we manage numbers of vaccine left until we get a
new factory on line and can start cranking it out,'' Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, he said, the supply is expected to
increase with vaccine from Bioport Corp.'s new manufacturing
facility in Lansing, Mich. Current supplies come only from
stockpiles produced by a small laboratory attached to the
University of Michigan, which manufactured only small quantities of
vaccine each year.
</P>
<P>
   After the Pentagon decided in 1998 to inoculate all 2.4 million
military personnel worldwide, the university sold the license to
Bioport as sole U.S. manufacturer of the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   But the new plant has had difficulties. An FDA inspection in
December cited more than 30 shortcomings that must be resolved
before it is allowed to sell new batches of the vaccine to the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said the plant has been working to meet all
specifications for a new FDA inspection in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 2025 </TRAILER>
