<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crawford Part of Bulls' Future  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- As Tim Floyd was watching Michigan play
basketball on TV one night, he noticed a quick guard with a
distinctive look wearing the Wolverines colors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw this guy running around with a headband and he got my
attention, but I didn't really study him because there were so many
good players on the floor,'' Floyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Floyd will get to watch that guard play right in front of
him every day in practice. Jamal Crawford is part of the Chicago
Bulls' future, a 20-year-old whose play in predraft camps
catapulted him into the top 10 of Wednesday night's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was doing an interview with Cleveland and they told me I'd
been traded and I thought they were kidding,'' said Crawford, who
was taken with the No. 8 pick by the Cavaliers and then traded to
the Bulls for the rights to Chris Mihm, selected by Chicago in the
seventh slot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told them I was going to wear a red suit,'' Crawford said,
reeling off the names of players on the rosters of the Bulls'
championship teams. ''Honestly, that's who I wanted to play for.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford spent nearly as much time on the Michigan bench last
season as he did on the floor. He played in only 17 games because
of two NCAA suspensions, averaging 16.6 points. Then he decided it
was time to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just one of those things we had to go through,''
Crawford's mother Venora said of last season. ''It kept us stronger
and it was something we had to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's Michigan teammates, in a show of support during one
game as their freshman leader was forced to sit out, all donned
headbands.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, from Seattle, took the look after seeing an old video
of former SuperSonics guard Slick Watts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I picked up on it and wanted to do something different and now
everybody is doing it,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford has a sense of NBA history, impressing Bulls GM Jerry
Krause by identifying players in old pictures on the wall of
Krause's office.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a picture of Earl Monroe and Wes Unseld and he knew
those guys. And I said, 'Wow, you're a basketball junkie' and sure
enough, he is,'' Krause said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, at 6-foot-6, will play point guard for the Bulls but
also can switch to shooting guard. His quickness, passing and
ability to create his own shot caught the Bulls' attention during
the NBA pre-draft camp in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've tried to take bits and pieces of everybody's game,''
Crawford said. ''Earl Monroe had that spin dribble move and I
remember seeing Slick. And being a big guard, big guards are at a
premium right now. The Lakers won a championship with big guards
like Ron Harper and Kobe Bryant. It's just the best time to be
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have a young nucleus. Crawford would be just a college
sophomore, fellow 2000 draftee Marcus Fizer a senior and last
year's top two picks Elton Brand and Ron Artest also college
seniors if they had not left early.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chicago, with approximately $20 million of room under the
salary cap, will go hunting for free agents when the negotiating
period begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The young players are an attraction,'' Krause said. ''The
veteran free agents know who the young players are, they know the
ones who can play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 2029 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sammy Sosa Trade Winds Die Down  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Sammy Sosa is sleeping better now, and not just
because he's still a member of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cubs spent nine hours trying to get from Pittsburgh to
Milwaukee on Thursday night, Sosa was in a Pittsburgh hotel room.
Manager Don Baylor felt the stress caused by weeks of trade rumors
swirling around Sosa had earned the slugger a bit of extra rest.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Cubs sat at a Pennsylvania airport until 5 a.m. EDT
waiting for a mechanical problem to be fixed on their team
airplane, Sosa stayed overnight and joined the team on Friday
afternoon. The Cubs didn't arrive at their hotel in Milwaukee until
well after dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ''He earned a rest. He's had a long three weeks, but I think his
spirits are up now,'' Baylor said shortly after Sosa arrived at
County Stadium on Friday, an hour after most of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees ended their pursuit of Sosa on Thursday
when they acquired David Justice from the Cleveland Indians. But
the Yankees' departure from the trade picture doesn't mean Sosa is
staying in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cubs going nowhere for yet another season, they likely
will continue to try to trade Sosa, whose contract expires in 2001.
But the field of suitors for such an outsized, soon-to-be
high-priced talent as Sosa could be non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible suitors for Sosa are Toronto, Cleveland and
the New York Mets, but it would take an extraordinary combination
of players and prospects to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   At least one observer thinks Sosa will be with Chicago for the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a one-market situation,'' first baseman Mark Grace
said. ''There was one team involved, and that team is no longer on
the market, so hopefully we can put this silliness behind us. I
think it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was changing into his uniform on Friday when Baylor stopped
by for a hug and a humorous chat about the travel problems. Sosa's
minor personality clashes with Baylor this season seem to be the
least of his worries now.
</P>
<P>
   He's still uncertain whether he'll be with the Cubs a month from
now when the trade deadline arrives. He only knows he won't be with
the Yankees, an idea to which he had warmed before the deal
abruptly died.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa didn't speak to reporters before the game, but he was
wearing his famous smile prior to the start of a three-game series
against the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's still focused,'' Baylor said. ''You can't get
through the home run race he went through without focus. He knows
how to be a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor acknowledged the trade rumors probably had a negative
effect on his team, which had lost eight of its last 10 before
Friday night. The Cubs had planned a team meeting for Friday to
address the problem, but they held it in Pittsburgh late Thursday
night when they found all kinds of time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know where those (trade) talks are going to go, but
right now he's on this ballclub and he wants to win,'' Baylor said.
''I think now it's time to finally put this aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's play has suffered since the Cubs, off to yet another
dismal season, began to consider trading their star. He went
5-for-23 over the last week in the middle six games of the Cubs'
12-game road trip, and he struck out in his first at-bat on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   While Sosa tries to get his stroke back, the Cubs will try to
play through the massive distraction caused by daily Sosa status
updates. Among the topics addressed at the Cubs' team meeting was
the likelihood that Chicago isn't through talking about losing
Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would imagine it would probably resurface,'' Baylor said.
''I don't think we've heard the last of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 2031 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury ends second day of deliberations in Quads' Mom trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) - A jury ended a second day of deliberations
Friday without a verdict in the trial of a South Texas millionaire
accused of arranging the 1997 Florida shooting and stabbing of his
ex-wife, the mother of 2-year-old quadruplets.
</P>
<P>
   The panel got the case on Thursday after three weeks of
testimony in U.S. District Court and deliberated for two hours.
Friday, jurors deliberated for eight more hours before breaking for
the weekend. The jury will return at 9 a.m. CDT on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Blackthorne, 45, is charged with interstate conspiracy to
commit murder-for-hire and with interstate domestic violence. He
faces a mandatory life sentence if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Bellush was killed on Nov. 7, 1997, about two months
after moving with her second husband and six children to Sarasota,
Fla. The quadruplets from her second marriage were discovered
unharmed in the house, two of them crawling in their mother's
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, the jury requested two tapes - one dealing with
Bellush's arrest in September 1997 on a charge of child abuse. The
other is a compilation from various news programs concerning
Blackthorne's ex-wife that prosecutors said he mailed to two
private investigating companies to help track her down.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also requested a newspaper clipping from the San
Antonio Express News detailing Bellush's flight from Texas to
Florida when she moved.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors portrayed Blackthorne as a man who hated his ex-wife
and who, after a string of custody battles, turned his hatred into
a scheme to have her killed.
</P>
<P>
   Using Blackthorne's own words from earlier testimony, prosecutor
Richard Durbin repeated several times, ''He didn't hate Sheila
Bellush. He just hated the things she did.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, Bellush won custody of their youngest
daughter, Daryl, and left the state.
</P>
<P>
   That, Durbin said, led Blackthorne to hunt down his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Bellush and Blackthorne were divorced in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne testified Monday that he once became so upset after
a daughter fell out of a second-story window that he told Bellush
he would kill her if ''anything happens to my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne has denied accusations that during a trip to Oregon
he asked Daniel Rocha, a golfing buddy, to find a hit man to kill
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Rocha testified on the first day of the trial that he contacted
a friend, Sammy Gonzales, who hired his cousin, Jose Luis Del Toro,
the alleged gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gonzales and Rocha are serving prison terms in Florida for
solicitation of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro, 23, a former high school football star in Uvalde, is
scheduled for trial next month in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's second husband and his family are now living in
Sussex County, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 2035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000630.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers Submit Offer to Lindros  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Flyers submitted an $8.5
million qualifying offer to center Eric Lindros on Friday night,
preventing him from becoming an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, his career in jeopardy because of a series of
concussions, has until Aug. 1 to accept the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eric Lindros is one of the top players in the game and is an
integral part of the Flyers organization,'' said Bob Clarke, the
Flyers' president and general manager. ''We are hopeful that he
will enjoy a complete recovery and return to play hockey at the
high level to which we have become accustomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke also made an overture to Lindros personally, noting the
feud between the former captain and management.
</P>
<P>
   ''On a personal level, I greatly regret the extent to which the
relationship between myself and Eric and his family has
deteriorated,'' Clarke said. ''I intend to do whatever I can to try
to move this relationship onto a better course.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old center has had six concussions in his NHL
career, the most recent on a check by New Jersey's Scott Stevens in
Game 7 of the Eastern Conference finals on May 26.
</P>
<P>
   James Kelly, a concussion expert who has been treating Lindros
said in a report that the injury-plagued star should not play for
now, but can do light exercise, play golf and ride a bike.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has said he doesn't know when he can return to the ice
and is considering sitting out up to a full year. He even indicated
he might play in Europe where the style of play is less physical.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has played eight seasons with the Flyers following a
mammoth trade with Quebec that included six players, two
first-round draft choices and $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has made six All-Star teams and won an MVP award in
1995, but the Flyers lost in their only Stanley Cup final with him.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' time in Philadelphia has been marked by turmoil and
controversy, including reports that he once left tickets for
reputed Philadelphia mob boss Joseph ''Skinny Joey'' Merlino.
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with Clarke, his childhood hero, deteriorated
to a point this season where the two men didn't speak for months.
</P>
<P>
   The boiling point came after Lindros criticized the team's
medical staff for failing to diagnose his second concussion of the
season on March 4.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke then stripped Lindros of his captaincy, and the star was
ostracized from the team until he returned for Games 6 and 7 of the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke had an even bigger problem with Lindros' parents.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Carl and Bonnie Lindros of constantly meddling in the
team's affairs. He said Carl has called him and insisted the team
not trade for certain players for reasons ranging from the player
doesn't pass the puck enough or Eric doesn't like the player's
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want his mom and dad. We've had enough of them,''
Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the Lindros family and the Flyers
really began to sour after Lindros suffered a collapsed lung on
April 1, 1999, in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The potentially life-threatening injury was diagnosed the
following day, and Lindros and his family had little to no
confidence in the team's medical staff after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lindros said he wanted to remain with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love playing in this city. The fans in this city are
spectacular,'' he said last month in his most recent press
conference with the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 2041 </TRAILER>
