<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Auburn Coach Criticizes Pat Dye  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- Former Auburn coach Terry Bowden, who agreed
not to make derogatory comments about Auburn after resigning in
1998, had unflattering things to say about his predecessor, Pat
Dye, and influential trustee Bobby Lowder.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Auburn Plainsman, Bowden said Dye
should have ''retired and moved on'' rather than remain a figure at
the university. He said Auburn could begin solving its problems by
removing Lowder from the Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, whose comments were published Thursday by the school
paper, was interviewed June 23 at a football camp in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said Friday in a phone interview with The Associated
Press while on vacation in Florida, that he made the published
comments after growing tired of actions taken against him by
Lowder.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bobby Lowder's attorneys have done everything they can on a
monthly basis to remove me from my house, and I just found out that
everything about Terry Bowden's time at Auburn was removed from the
athletics museum. And I'm just getting tired of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really do love Auburn and want to be a part of this
community the rest of my life, but I do wonder when it's all going
to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   A settlement Bowden reached with Auburn when he resigned
included mortgage payments on his home at Auburn if he complied
with other terms of the agreement, such as his comments about the
university and work he might do in the sports world. He has been
doing football commentary for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   In the Plainsman interview, Bowden said: ''Coach Dye is not Bear
Bryant. He was only here 12 years. He never won a national
championship. Pat was a real successful coach, but he wasn't a
difficult act to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He should have retired and moved on, though,'' said Bowden.
''You can't stay around.''
</P>
<P>
   Dye, after resigning in 1992, remained in an administrative role
with the university and was quoted at times about his views of
Auburn football while Bowden was coach.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said it's disruptive to have a former coach on the scene
talking about his successor.
</P>
<P>
   ''People at Auburn want to love their current coach, so if the
old coach criticizes the new coach, then what are all those people
at Auburn supposed to believe?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowder, a wealthy Montgomery banker who was instrumental in
hiring both Dye and Bowden, was viewed by some as a
behind-the-scenes force pushing for Bowden's ouster in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remove Bobby Lowder from the Board of Trustees is the only way
you're going to fix Auburn,'' Bowden told the Plainsman. ''He
politically understands what he's doing. It's his nature to
micro-manage and control.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Dye's comments might have influenced Lowder to seek
Bowden's ouster, Bowden replied: ''You have to use your own
judgment. Bobby Lowder doesn't know a lick about football. Bobby
Lowder never came to my offices. He didn't have a clue as to
whether I was recruiting good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Bobby Lowder is only as good as those who inform him and give
him information,'' said Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, whose Tigers were 1-5 when he resigned in 1998, reached
a $620,000 settlement that among other things bars him from making
negative or derogatory comments ''toward Auburn, the Auburn
athletics department or its employees or the Auburn Board of
Trustees.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn athletics director David Housel, contacted Friday about
Bowden's published comments, said, ''We're looking ahead, not back.
We're getting ready for the 2000 season.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Lowder said he had no comment at this time.
Attempts to reach Dye were unsuccessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
