<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ACLU Sues Over Convention Access  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A coalition of activists bent on capturing
the attention of Democratic National Convention delegates sued the
city and police department on Friday for greater access to the
August event site.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities plan to have a buffer zone around the Staples Center
and the Los Angeles Convention Center and set up demonstration
areas with a stage and sound system on the opposite side of the
centers' giant parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs claim there is no way delegates would ever see or
hear protesters from that location. Daniel P. Tokaji, of the
American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California, said that
violates the protesters' free speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU filed the lawsuit on behalf of a Service Employees
International Union local; a group organizing protesters;
supporters of Mumia Abu-Jamal, who was convicted of killing a
police officer; a National Lawyers Guild chapter; an editor of a
newspaper for the poor and homeless; and a state legislator.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Austin, spokesman for the convention host committee, said
the demonstration area gives activists ''easy access to the
delegates and the residents of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We put it right square in front of the Staples Center so we
could engage in a dialogue,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
