<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy clears way to tow battleship New Jersey to Camden  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - The USS New Jersey, which will be converted
into a floating museum, could be turned over to Camden and the
group that will renovate the warship as early as mid-July, Rep. Jim
Saxton said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''At last, the Big J is coming home,'' Saxton said Friday in a
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton, R-Mount Holly, who helped lead the Camden campaign, said
Navy officials told him an environmental study about the ship being
permanently docked in Camden had been sent to the federal
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is a contract between the Navy and the Home Port
Alliance, the group that will run the museum, to turn over the
ship, Saxton said. Then the Navy's most highly decorated warship
will be towed to Camden.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything seems to be falling into place,'' said retired Rear
Adm. Tom Seigenthaler, project director of the Home Port Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely the ship will be towed to the South Jersey Port off
Beckett Street, Saxton said.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office is expected to complete a review
of the ship docking in Camden in August. But the results of that
study aren't expected to change the outcome, Saxton said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-Ridgewood, in March asked the General
Accounting Office to review the Navy's decision. She had supported
a competing plan to bring the ship to Bayonne, across the harbor
from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Both cities want to host the battleship in hopes that tourists
will flock to a battleship museum.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of commission members favored putting the battleship
at the former Military Ocean Terminal in Bayonne, with the option
of moving it to Liberty State Park in Jersey City if the park's
waterfront were renovated to accommodate the huge vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig in January announced the
battleship, a decorated veteran of four military conflicts, would
spend its retirement off Camden, just across the Delaware River
from the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard. The ship was built
there early in World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 2054 </TRAILER>
