<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor signs bill to repeal hidden gas tax increase before it can take effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman on Friday signed into
law a bill repealing a new but small gasoline tax increase before
it could take effect.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 law set a special tax of 2.75 percent on the wholesale
price of petroleum products, which resulted in an extra 4-cent tax
on gasoline above and beyond the state's standard 10.5-cent
gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   Because the wholesale petroleum tax was based on a rate of 2.75
percent, higher gasoline prices mean a higher tax. With gas prices
now going above $1.50 a gallon, the 1991 law would have driven the
4-cent tax rate higher by tiny increments starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If the gas price were to reach an average of $1.50 a gallon, the
tax would have increased by 1 cent on every 10 gallons of gas. But
should the price reach $2, the tax increase would have reached 1.5
cents per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The bill Whitman signed locked the wholesale tax rate for
gasoline at 4 cents per gallon, no matter what the gas price is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 2056 </TRAILER>
