<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court expands voting rights for those who choose write-in candidates </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Supreme Court on Friday ordered
sweeping and possibly costly changes in New Jersey voting
procedures to remove barriers for voters who want to cast their
ballot for a write-in candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It all came about because of a lawsuit brought by three people
who ran for office in the tiny borough of Chesilhurst in November
as write-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Such candidates are rarely given much of a chance of winning,
but in Chesilhurst, where only 411 people voted on Nov. 2, the
write-in votes could have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent mayor, Arland Poindexter, won with 172 votes over
write-in candidate Kati Gray-Sadler with 152 votes. However, at
least two dozen votes for Gray-Sadler had been ruled invalid,
according to the court opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Some votes were invalidated because the voters wrote
Gray-Sadler's name on the wrong line. Others were invalidated
because the voters used stickers with the candidates' names on them
that the voting machines evidently stripped off.
</P>
<P>
   Gray-Sadler and two other candidates who ran for borough council
seats filed a lawsuit after they lost the election complaining they
were denied a fair chance.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court dismissed their claim in February, issuing
a half-page opinion saying Poindexter could keep his seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Justice Deborah Poritz landed powerfully on the side
of the little guy on Friday, reversing the appeals court in an
unanimous ruling that ordered Chesilhurst to do it all over in a
special election in August.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Poritz's sweeping decision strengthened the
rights of voters who prefer write-in candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In their legal filings, lawyers for Camden County said the
county elections board might have to spend more than $4 million to
upgrade election machines to make it easier to write in candidates'
names or to affix stickers provided by their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the ruling could require refurbishing or replacement of
voting machines in Monmouth, Essex, Cape May, Passaic, Hudson,
Mercer and Cumberland counties, according to The Philadelphia
Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   But Poritz ruled that Chesilhurst's voters who wanted to select
a write-in candidate on Nov. 2 faced too many pitfalls, and as a
result ''qualified voters were disenfranchised.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, sample ballots mailed to all voters lacked
instructions on how to write in a candidate's name.
</P>
<P>
   The ballots inside the voting booth had instructions printed in
small type instructing the voter to use the ''personal choice''
lever for a write-in candidate, but the location of that lever was
not marked on the voting machine.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions also told the voter to seek help from
polling-place volunteers if they were confused. The problem is,
once the voter closes the curtain behind them, they cannot reopen
it without automatically casting all of their votes.
</P>
<P>
   And the ballot also had tricky instructions requiring a voter to
hold down a lever with one hand in order to open the small window
in which the voter was then supposed to write the candidate's name
with the other hand.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting her legendary predecessor, former Chief Justice Arthur
T. Vanderbilt, in a 1952 ruling, Poritz said, ''We have held that
it is our duty to construe election laws liberally.'' She said
these laws must be enforced to make sure that every person's vote
counts fully and is not diluted no matter which candidate they
choose.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://lawlibrary.rutgers.edu/search.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 2106 </TRAILER>
