<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Welcomes Anti-Drug Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW SELSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's defense minister on Friday
applauded Washington's stepped-up role in battling the country's
cocaine and heroin producers who are protected by leftist rebels
and right-wing paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good news,'' Defense Minister Luis Fernando Ramirez said
of the passage by Congress of a bill earlier Friday that would
provide $1.3 billion, mostly to equip and train Colombian security
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''They realize ... that the United States must actively link
itself directly to the fight against drug trafficking, like we
expect the rest of the international community will do,'' Ramirez
told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which President Bill Clinton said Friday he would
sign, will provide Colombian security forces with 42 upgraded
Vietnam-era Huey and 18 Blackhawk helicopters. Colombian troops --
trained by the United States -- would use the choppers to seize
control of coca- and poppy-growing areas and allow low-flying
planes to eliminate the crops by fumigation.
</P>
<P>
   Two more special army battalions would be trained by Green
Berets and other U.S. Special Forces under the aid package. One
950-man anti-narcotics battalion has already been trained and is
expected to soon begin helicopter-borne operations from its base in
Tres Esquinas, in southern Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the three battalions, the army will be able to secure the
area where the fumigations will occur,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Western nations to do more by reducing drug
consumption, control the export of so-called precursor chemicals
used in cocaine production, halt black-market arms shipments to
armed groups in Colombia, and to drop trade barriers that impede
access of Colombian goods such as sugar, bananas and textiles to
international markets.
</P>
<P>
   The latter move would induce Colombian farmers stop growing coca
and poppies -- used to make cocaine and heroin respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's main rebel group, meanwhile, hosted foreign diplomats
for the second day in a rebel-held area ceded by the government as
part of a peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference in the town of Los Pozos, Manuel ''Sureshot''
Marulanda, chief of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, met
with representatives of 21 countries and spoke of possible prisoner
exchanges, human rights, drug production and distribution, and
other topics, said Simon Trinidad, a rebel spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   However, during the two-day conference which ended Friday, some
diplomats took aim at human rights violations by the rebel group,
known by its Spanish acronym as the FARC.
</P>
<P>
   British Ambassador Jeremy Thorp and Belgian Ambassador Jean Paul
Warnimont asked the FARC to suspend its kidnappings and extorsions
-- which the rebels have used to raise funds -- to stop recruiting
children into its ranks, to stop planting land mines and to halt
attacks on civilian populations, according to press reports from
the site of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Thorp also reportedly asked the rebels to make peace gestures,
such as a cease-fire, and to halt to its well-paid drug-protection
operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 2117 </TRAILER>
