<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aircraft subcontractor admits sending substandard parts to assembler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The general manager of a Boeing Co.
subcontractor admitted Friday that he sent substandard metal parts
to a Canadian aviation manufacturer, and then falsified papers
certifying that the parts were up to par.
</P>
<P>
   The parts, called bracket covers, were destined for use on
Boeing 757s but were probably not installed, said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Mark Winston, who is prosecuting the case.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, based in Seattle, could not immediately determine what
happened to the bracket covers, spokeswoman Vicki Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   David Taeschler, the general manager of Tam Metal Products in
Mahwah, pleaded guilty to a single charge of conspiracy to commit
wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Taeschler, 39, of Ramsey, faces up to five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine when sentenced Sept. 27 by U.S. District Judge Mary
L. Cooper. The actual penalties would be far less, under federal
sentencing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Tam got an order for the bracket covers in October 1996 from
Menasco Aerospace, of Oakville, Ontario, which was to use them in
landing gear for the 757s, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing required that the covers be heat-treated by an authorized
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Tam sent Menasco covers that had not been treated after a
Menasco employee told Taeschler that Menasco would get them treated
in Canada, Taeschler said. He did not name the employee.
</P>
<P>
   The employee later told Taeschler that Menasco could not get the
parts treated in Canada, and that he must send proof of heat
treatment or Menasco could not sell the parts to Boeing, Taeschler
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Taeschler sent Menasco faxes of fabricated certifications,
falsely showing the work had been done at a Boeing-approved company
in Brooklyn, N.Y., Hercules Heat Treating Corp., he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Heat treatment is used to harden some metal parts, and to make
others softer. Its use in this application was not immediately
available, Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Menasco could not be reached for comment because its offices
were closed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is continuing, Winston said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
