<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bucks man makes bail in dancer's death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOUNT HOLLY, N.J. (AP) - A Pennsylvania businessman charged in
Burlington County, N.J., in connection with the March 29 death of
an exotic dancer posted bond Friday after a judge reduced his bail
to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   John Denofa, 35, of Buckingham, had been in jail on a $1 million
bond, charged with killing 21-year-old Rachel Siani. Siani's
crumpled body was found April 1 under the New Jersey side of a
bridge that connects the New Jersey and Pennsylvania turnpikes.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Superior Court Judge John A. Sweeney agreed Thursday
to reduce Denofa's bond, but ordered him to surrender his passport,
sign an affidavit not to fight extradition to New Jersey, and meet
weekly with a probation officer.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 of Denofa's friends and relatives appeared at the
hearing; some are helping him post bond. Denofa participated in the
hearing from jail by way of closed-circuit television, but did not
make any remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Siani, who lived in Bensalem, had worked at Divas International
Gentleman's Club in Bristol Township. Denofa, who is married, was a
Tuesday night regular and often stayed in the adjoining Econo
Lodge, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Siani was last seen with Denofa at about 2 a.m. March 29 in the
club's parking lot. Police believe that he choked her in a motel
room until she was unconscious, threw her out a window and then put
her in the back of his truck. He then drove to the turnpike, where
she was thrown over the bridge, police charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have people who want to believe in something that's really
a fairy tale,'' First Assistant Burlington County Prosecutor
Raymond Milavsky said at Thursday's hearing. ''This is the real
Jack Denofa. ... Anyone who is capable of this is capable of
flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have said that blood, hair and fibers consistent with
Siani's clothing were found in Denofa's pickup truck. Prosecutors
have a grainy video of what appears to be a body sprawled in the
bed of the truck as it entered a New Jersey Turnpike toll plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers argued Thursday that three autopsies performed
on the victim's body showed three different causes of death.
</P>
<P>
   Denofa was originally jailed in Bucks County, but was moved to
Burlington County earlier this month after a Bucks County judge
ruled there was sufficient evidence that Siani was killed in New
Jersey. Police believe she died of injuries sustained in the
200-foot fall from the bridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
