<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
8 Dead in Denmark Pearl Jam Concert
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Fans rushed the stage during a Pearl Jam concert
at one of Europe's largest rock festivals Friday, crushing to death at least
eight people and injuring three others. Members of Pearl Jam implored the crowd
to move back because people were being pressed up against the stage, and the
message was repeated over the loudspeakers, Danish radio said. The American band
halted its performance and the following performance by The Cure was canceled.
But concerts on the festival's six other stages continued, a festival spokesman
said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Perot Shuns Bid for President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Two-time presidential candidate Ross Perot today turned down
backer' efforts to put his name on the Reform Party's primary ballot, removing a
potential hurdle for Pat Buchanan's bid. The Texas billionaire decided against
running in the primary because he had no intention of actually competing for the
White House in November, Russell Verney, Perot's spokesman, said. Verney said
Perot didn't want to put his name on the Reform ballot only to stop Buchanan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ark. Court Panel Files Vs. Clinton
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- An Arkansas Supreme Court committee today sued
President Clinton to strip him of his law license, declaring he lacked ''overall
fitness'' to be a lawyer. The panel accused Clinton of serious misdeeds in the
Monica Lewinsky affair, including false testimony. ''The conduct of Mr. Clinton
... was motivated by a desire to protect himself from the embarrassment of his
own conduct,'' the court's Committee on Professional Conduct wrote. Clinton has
30 days to respond, and his private attorney vowed a vigorous fight to retain
the law license.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Can't Find E-Mails
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House has yet to recover any missing e-mails
sought by investigators, a judge disclosed today, but it is turning over backup
tapes that might contain the messages to Independent Counsel Robert Ray and the
Justice Department. Two law enforcement officials told The Associated Press that
the FBI will now step in and try to retrieve the missing e-mails. Congress, Ray
and Justice are investigating whether the e-mail problem was an innocent
mistake, as the White House contends, or part of an effort to obstruct their
investigations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't To Limit UC Role at Los Alamos
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a string of security lapses, the Energy Department
gave notice today that it intends to strip the University of California of its
security and some management responsibilities involving nuclear weapons programs
at Los Alamos and another government research lab. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson told the university its contracts for managing the Los Alamos and
Lawrence Livermore labs ''must be restructured ... to make much-needed
improvements to security.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hanford Fire Dying Out
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- The wildfire that raced across nearly half of the
Hanford nuclear complex was all but extinguished Friday, and Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson gave assurances that the flames did not spread radiation. The
190,000-acre blaze, which was ignited by sparks from an auto wreck and exploded
into a 30-mph inferno in less than a day. It burned 45 percent of the
560-square-mile reservation plus 20 homes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congress Passes $11.2B Spending Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though President Clinton requested a package half the
size, Congress today completed an $11.2 billion measure financing Colombia's war
against drugs, Pentagon needs and U.S. disaster aid. The Senate gave final
approval to the bill by voice vote and lawmakers left town for their weeklong
July Fourth recess. The House assented to the bill on Thursday night, 306-110.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FCC To Study Internet Access
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission is looking at
whether old rules designed to break open the local Bell monopolies extend to new
Web services still in their infancy. The FCC's review could have implications
for the long-running debate over whether cable Internet providers must give
other online companies access to their lines. So far, the commission has
declined to impose such a requirement, fearing that any regulation would slow
the growth of the emerging market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 50; Nasdaq Climbs 89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rallying in the final hour of trading, the Dow Jones
industrial average erased a small loss today and finished up 49.85 at 10,447.89
in heavy trading. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by a narrow margin. The Nasdaq
composite index, lifted by computer chips and semiconducter stocks, rose 88.88
to 3,966.11.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tickets.com To Sell MLB Tickets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) -- Tickets.com will become major league baseball's
online ticket vendor beginning in the 2001 season. Under the deal announced
Friday, Tickets.com will handle ticket sales at each of the Web sites run by
baseball's 30 teams.
</P>
