<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developer builds hotel over allowed specifications  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) - They probably won't be sleeping on the
street, but the Minnesota delegation to the Republican National
Convention doesn't have a place to stay. The luxury hotel they were
to occupy has not opened because county government officials say
it's too big.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation was going to fill 150 of the 191 rooms at the
six-story Radisson Plaza Suites Hotel, but now has no place to stay
when they arrive in Philadelphia for the GOP convention from July
31 to Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was really looking forward to the Jacuzzis in the rooms. I
heard they had them in the king suites,'' Minnesota delegate
Margaret Cavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still want the Minnesota delegation to come to Delaware,''
said J. Harry Feldman, spokesman for the Greater Wilmington
Convention and Visitors Bureau. ''We have some very nice properties
that are only 10 minutes farther away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota GOP said Delaware tourism officials called
Wednesday to say the rooms were in jeopardy. The Republican
National Committee assigned convention groups to their hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this time, we're sort of letting it work itself out,'' GOP
convention spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   New Castle County land use officials say they won't grant the
Radisson an occupancy permit because the finished hotel is bigger
than originally proposed - possibly as much as 39,000 square feet
larger.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, that makes the imposing-looking hotel near
Interstate 95 illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors for New Castle County found numerous inconsistencies
with a building plan filed in 1990. State law prevents any
certificate of occupancy from being awarded to a building that does
not comply with its own filed plan.
</P>
<P>
   The original plans approved a 118,805 square-foot building, but
the developers are now seeking a permit for a 158,176 square-foot
building - 39,371 square feet more than the plans called for.
</P>
<P>
   That new permit is among a dozen requests by the developers,
including Joseph L. Capano Sr. and Albert A. Vietri, to bypass
regulations and make the building legal.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for Capano and Vietri said the discrepancies
between the steel-and-concrete structure and the plans on paper are
due more to stupidity than dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, you probably couldn't count on both hands and feet
how many people blew it on this thing,'' said attorney Larry
Tarabicos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 2122 </TRAILER>
