<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key witness in Gravano case had planned to kill Gravano, witness says </HEADLINE>
By ELISA BONGIOVANNI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) - An Arizona man that was granted full immunity to
testify against Salvatore ''Sammy the Bull'' Gravano had once
plotted to kill the former Mafia underboss, a witness testified in
Maricopa County Superior Court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Edwin Sr., 44, testified at a bond reduction hearing for
Gravano that he became of aware of key witness Phillip Pascucci's
murder plot against Gravano in December 1997. Edwin said Pascucci
and friend Howard Fishman had a $1 million bounty on Gravano and
had planned to lure him to a poker game and kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believed after the second conversation it was real,'' Edwin
said. ''I believed in my heart they were serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravano, who was in court Friday to try to reduce his $5 million
bond, is accused of being the brains and bankroller of Arizona's
largest ecstasy syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Pascucci, who lives in Scottsdale, was arrested June 12 on a
federal drug warrant out of San Antonio, Texas. Pascucci then began
implicating that he had sold large amounts of the drug ecstasy to
Gravano and was recruited by him for a murder plot.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Donald Conrad says that Pascucci, an
ex-convict, had sold 7,000 ecstasy pills to Gravano from late 1998
through February of this year, when the former hit-man was arrested
in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Conrad claims that Pascucci can describe how
Gravano plotted to kill attorney Ron Kuby who organized a
multi-million dollar lawsuit for families of the 19 people Gravano
murdered as a member of the Gambino crime family in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano admitted killing the 19, but he testified against its
boss, John Gotti, and served just five years in prison. Gotti is
serving a life sentence. When Gravano was released from prison in
1995, he entered the witness protection program, using the name
Jimmy Moran. He dropped out by early 1997. Prior to his arrest, he
had been living in suburban Tempe, near his family.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin further testified that 35-year-old Pascucci had said that
if he ever got into trouble he would just ''roll over on Gravano''
- in other words, turn on him.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad said that Edwin's testimony against Pascucci should be
taken with ''a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It shouldn't surprise you that this was just another murder
plot for Mr. Gravano,'' Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano's Attorney Larry Hammond said that Pascucci is not a
credible witness because of his criminal history and the fact that
he didn't implicate Gravano until his third interview with police.
According to court documents, Pascucci was interviewed twice by
Phoenix police detectives four months before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the bond reduction, Hammond said Gravano is not a
flight risk because he and his family have too much at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything this family does is front page news,'' he said.
''This is a man that should be with his family and have the
opportunity to defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Steven Sheldon is not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even assuming the evidence cuts both ways, this man could be
in an Arizona jail until his 60s,'' he said. ''I am not convinced
he wouldn't want to take that alternative (and run).''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon took the case under advisement and is expected to rule
within five to ten days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-30-00 2202 </TRAILER>
