<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ricky Ledee Set To Help Indians  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Ricky Ledee says he is over the shock of being
traded.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was sad when it happened, but I see this as an opportunity
and I am ready,'' Ledee said Friday after taking batting practice
for the first time as a member of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, 26, was dealt to Cleveland by the New York Yankees for
outfielder David Justice on Thursday night. The Indians have until
Aug. 1 to select two minor-league prospects from a list provided by
the Yankees to complete the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, wearing No. 22, was in the starting lineup against the
Minnesota Twins as the left fielder, batting seventh. He went
1-for-3 with a walk in a 7-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard rumors of a trade and the last place I thought it
would be was Cleveland,'' Ledee said. ''I was surprised, but then I
thought about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm coming to a team with a lot of talent, a team that has
been a consistent winner and wants to keep winning. It's a good
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Still, I wasn't prepared for it. I spent 11 years in the
Yankees organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade left the Indians clubhouse a bit confused.
</P>
<P>
   ''It kind of shocked everybody,'' pitcher Dave Burba said. ''The
general consensus is that there is more going on.
</P>
<P>
   ''To take the RBI leader out of your lineup, there has to be
more to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice, 34, had 58 RBIs in 68 games with 21 home runs and a
.265 average. Ledee batted. .241 with seven homers and 31 RBIs in
62 games with New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ricky has a definite upside,'' Indians manager Charlie Manuel
said. ''I'm going to put him in the lineup against all pitching and
see what he can do. I remember him getting some big hits off our
lefties last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the field, I want to see him play center and might even put
him over in right field, too. I understand he can play all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel again dismissed suggestions that the deal meant
Cleveland, 8&AMP;frac12; games behind the first-place Chicago White Sox, were
giving up on a chance of winning a sixth consecutive AL Central
title.
</P>
<P>
   ''Looking at where we are and where we want to be, this deal is
definitely a positive,'' Manuel said. ''We still need a few more
things, a starting pitcher, some help in the bullpen and maybe
another hitter, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like the way Ricky swings the bat. I think he can help us
get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
