<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Champlain border improvements discussed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHAMPLAIN, N.Y. (AP) - Reacting to fatal crashes and
consistently snarled traffic, officials have laid out options to
improve the Champlain crossing between the U.S. and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   It will be summer of 2003 before the $23 million improvement
plan can begin at the Champlain border facility, the U.S. General
Services Administration said Thursday. In a briefing at the border,
GSA staff outlined four alternative designs for revamping the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Long waits to pass through Customs and dangerously congested
traffic were seen as a hindrance to growing trade with Canada and
economic growth in the corridor between Montreal and the
Champlain/Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers said all options include expansion of
passenger-vehicle lanes, additional truck lanes, more parking,
expansion of the main building, reconfiguration and improvements to
the bus-processing area, a building for inspection of animals and
plants, a separate Immigration and Naturalization Services
inspection area and consolidation of broker/cargo services.
</P>
<P>
   Interim improvements include signs as far as eight miles out on
the Canadian side warning of possible congestion.
</P>
<P>
   The interim plan also includes rumble strips and message boards
to warn of congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the cost, the major changes must be approved by
Congress, a move that is not likely until fall 2002. A contract
could be awarded in October or November of that year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
