<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Countries Approve War Tribunal  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- More than 100 countries approved two
documents for world's first permanent war crimes tribunal Friday --
a move the United States said was a step toward exempting Americans
from prosecution by the court.
</P>
<P>
   But with the United States clearly in mind, many countries
warned that they will oppose any changes to the 1998 Rome treaty
creating the International Criminal Court -- and any interpretation
of its rules that makes a dispensation for one country.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Rome statute is here to stay and it cannot and will not be
changed,'' declared Philippe Kirsch, chairman of the commission
preparing for the court's operation, just before closing the
three-week meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The strong statements from countries ranging from the European
Union to New Zealand and Angola set the stage for tough
negotiations at the commission's next meeting starting in November,
when the United States is hoping to win final agreement for an
exemption.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. effort ''to undermine the court'' has failed at this
session, said Richard Dicker, associate counsel for Human Rights
Watch. ''But governments will have to prepare for another assault
in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief U.S. negotiator David Scheffer, the ambassador-at-large
for war crimes issues, denied that the United States was trying to
change the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just very satisfied with the outcome of this,'' he said,
referring to the approval of the documents. ''It is a long journey.
We've taken another step and we'll take some more steps as the
months go by.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States was one of seven countries voting ''no'' when
120 countries meeting in Rome approved the treaty to establish the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   What the United States objects to is that American citizens can
be subject to the court's jurisdiction if an alleged crime is
committed in a country that has ratified the treaty -- even if the
United States is not a party. Washington says this would leave U.S.
troops and citizens vulnerable to politically motivated
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the U.S. stand on the treaty, it has been a key player
in 18 months of negotiations that culminated Friday with agreement
on the two documents: on rules of procedure for the court; and on
elements that constitute crimes against humanity, war crimes and
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer likened the first document, the elements of crime, to a
checklist that will be used to determine whether a person has
committed such crimes as sexual slavery and torture.
</P>
<P>
   The rules of procedure cover a wide spectrum, but the United
States focused particularly on one rule dealing with conditions
under which the court may request the surrender of a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. view, Scheffer said, the rule agreed on Friday does
not prevent the court from entering a separate international
agreement with a country on the surrender of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   This is ''the gateway,'' he said, for a proposal the United
States expects to make at the commission's next meeting to exempt
Americans from prosecution as long as the United States has not
ratified the treaty. The U.S. proposal will also address concerns
of the European Union and other nations that an exemption for the
United States could not be used by ''irresponsible nations,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what we're negotiating right now, but that's for
November-December,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 2232 </TRAILER>
