<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Principal Hikes for Students  </HEADLINE>
By GARRY MITCHELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROEVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- A principal who helped save a tiny
Alabama school battled fatigue and blistered feet Friday as she
finished a 54-mile, 18-hour trek along Alabama back roads to
celebrate her students' academic turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Robinson left Monroe Senior High School in remote
Packers Bend on Thursday night, accompanied by 40 supporters,
including parents and students, and headed for the county seat of
Monroeville.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lord Jesus, I thought I was going to stop. The hill at Perdue
Hill nearly killed me,'' Robinson said before noon Friday, stopping
at a store to treat a blister. ''I'm afraid of rats and snakes, and
when it was dark, it was mighty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But she made it back to Monroeville on Friday afternoon, less
than 17 hours after departing, and proclaimed: ''I'm feeling
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Monroe has only 108 students in kindergarten through 12th grade
-- a dramatic drop from the more the 500 it had in the 1980s -- and
its high school is the smallest in the state with 54 students.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson, a 40-year-old fifth-grade teacher, was made
principal in 1997, the school was filthy, morale was low, test
scores were abysmal and the Monroe County school board threatened
to close it.
</P>
<P>
   But at Robinson's urging, students at the 70-year-old, all-black
school studied through longer school days and on frequent
Saturdays, and their test scores -- and pride in their school --
began to rise.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the school's eight seniors all graduated, and four
have earned college scholarships. The school is now a showplace,
Monroe School Superintendent Dennis Mixon said.
</P>
<P>
   The final victory came when the school was removed from academic
caution and given clear status by the state Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ''To say black kids can't do it because of poverty is wrong,''
Robinson said. ''You can't get any poorer than here. Kids can do it
if someone believes in them.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is to let my students know that in life there are going
to be some hard roads and in order for you to achieve these goals
you have to continue to work at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-30-00 2241 </TRAILER>
