<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.C. Pulls Plug on Most Video Poker  </HEADLINE>
By DAN LEWERENZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Fourteen years after video gambling became
legal in South Carolina, the plug was being pulled on nearly all
the machines because of a statewide ban that was to take effect at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled in dark, smoky rooms Friday, players' reaction on video
gambling's final day was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bored. That's what I'm going to be -- bored,'' said Wanda Rose,
playing at the Double Diamond in Columbia. ''I mean, it's my money.
I think that I should be able to spend it however I want.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who owns five casinos in South Carolina won a temporary
injunction from a Circuit Court judge allowing him -- and only him --
to keep his video poker machines running for 10 days, until a
hearing on his challenge to the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Charlie Condon said he told state and local law
enforcement officers to obey the order ''if it appears valid'' but
sought to have it overturned late Friday by the state Supreme
Court, which had already denied other requests for emergency
injunctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just one poker baron asking this judge to stop the
enforcement of a valid state order,'' Condon said. ''This raises a
very serious question of judicial accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Video poker became legal in South Carolina after a lawmaker
slipped a provision into a bill; it eventually became a $3 billion
annual industry.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-gambling forces fought hard to outlaw the machines, a
battle that came to a head in 1998 when then-Gov. David Beasley, a
Republican, called video gambling ''a cancer on South Carolina''
and vowed to get rid of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Video gambling operators responded by pouring money into the
campaign of Democrat Jim Hodges, who won the governor's race with a
promise to call for a referendum on video gambling's future.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature last year approved the referendum as part of a
bill that also banned video gambling unless voters decided to keep
the machines. Last October, the state Supreme Court threw out the
referendum, but kept the part of the law banning video gambling on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   State officials planned to check machines early Saturday to make
sure they are turned off. Operators have one week to get the
machines out of the state or destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm glad it's out,'' Margaret Perry said Friday as she played
at D J's Video Games in Columbia. ''It's caused a lot of problems
in my life. It's been a detriment to my spiritual life. I hate
myself for this, for what I've done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
