<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
100 Countries Approve War Tribunal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- More than 100 countries approved two documents for the
world's first permanent war crimes tribunal today -- a move the United States
said was a step toward exempting Americans from prosecution by the court. But
with the United States clearly in mind, many countries warned that they will
oppose any changes to the 1998 Rome treaty creating the International Criminal
Court -- and any interpretation of its rules that makes a dispensation for one
country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ark. Court Sues To Disbar Clinton
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- An Arkansas Supreme Court committee sued President
Clinton today to strip him of his law license and declared he lacked ''overall
fitness'' to be a lawyer. The committee's lawsuit accused the president of
engaging in serious misconduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair, including false
testimony, that ''damages the legal profession.'' The five-page lawsuit asks
that Clinton be disbarred for conducting ''himself in a manner that violates the
model rules of professional conduct as adopted by the Arkansas Supreme Court.''
The president has 30 days to respond, and his private attorney vowed a vigorous
fight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
8 Dead in Denmark Pearl Jam Concert
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- At least eight people were crushed to death and
three others were injured Friday when fans rushed the stage during a Pearl Jam
concert at one of Europe's largest rock festivals. Members of Pearl Jam had
urged the crowd to move back because people were being pressed up against the
stage, and the warning was repeated on loudspeakers, Danish radio said. The band
halted its performance and the following session by The Cure was canceled. But
concerts on six other stages went on, a festival spokesman said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Perot Shuns Bid for President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Two-time presidential candidate Ross Perot today turned down
backer' efforts to put his name on the Reform Party's primary ballot, removing a
potential hurdle for Pat Buchanan's bid. The Texas billionaire decided against
running in the primary because he had no intention of actually competing for the
White House in November, Russell Verney, Perot's spokesman, said. Verney said
Perot didn't want to put his name on the Reform ballot only to stop Buchanan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Can't Find E-Mails
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House has yet to recover any missing e-mails
sought by investigators, a judge disclosed today, but it is turning over backup
tapes that might contain the messages to Independent Counsel Robert Ray and the
Justice Department. Two law enforcement officials told The Associated Press that
the FBI will now step in and try to retrieve the missing e-mails. Congress, Ray
and Justice are investigating whether the e-mail problem was an innocent
mistake, as the White House contends, or part of an effort to obstruct their
investigations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't To Limit UC Role at Los Alamos
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a string of security lapses, the Energy Department
gave notice today that it intends to strip the University of California of its
security and some management responsibilities involving nuclear weapons programs
at Los Alamos and another government research lab. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson told the university its contracts for managing the Los Alamos and
Lawrence Livermore labs ''must be restructured ... to make much-needed
improvements to security.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congress Passes $11.2B Spending Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though President Clinton requested a package half the
size, Congress today completed an $11.2 billion measure financing Colombia's war
against drugs, Pentagon needs and U.S. disaster aid. The Senate gave final
approval to the bill by voice vote and lawmakers left town for their weeklong
July Fourth recess. The House assented to the bill on Thursday night, 306-110.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 50; Nasdaq Climbs 89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rallying in the final hour of trading, the Dow Jones
industrial average today erased a small loss and finished up 49.85 at 10,447.89
in heavy trading. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by a narrow margin. The Nasdaq
composite index, lifted by computer chips and semiconducter stocks, rose 88.88
to 3,966.11.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Rally to Defeat Braves 11-8
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Piazza capped a 10-run, eighth-inning comeback with a
tiebreaking, three-run homer off Terry Mulholland, and the New York Mets stunned
the Atlanta Braves 11-8 tonight. John Rocker, the controversial reliever who has
become New York's No. 1 villain, remained in the bullpen as Kevin Millwood
handed an 8-1 lead to Atlanta's bullpen, only to watch Don Wengert, Kerry
Ligtenberg and Mulholland (8-7) fritter it away, forcing in three runs with
bases-loaded walks.
</P>
