<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kansas' Williams Fate Not Decided  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG TUCKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Roy Williams is pleading for patience as
two of the nation's premier basketball programs and their fans
await word from the winningest coach of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Should he stay at his beloved Kansas or return to his beloved
North Carolina?
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina coach Bill Guthridge retired Friday, just three
seasons after following Dean Smith, the winningest college
basketball coach of all time. Williams, who had been an assistant
to Smith before taking over at Kansas in 1988, appears to be the
No. 1 candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   He denied an Associated Press report that he had already agreed
to take over the Tar Heels' job. A source familiar with the
university and speaking on condition of anonymity told the AP that
Williams would be the next coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people in North Carolina don't really know what I have
here,'' Williams told a packed news conference on the Kansas campus
Friday evening. ''The people here don't realize what I'd have in
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing I'm saying is give me a little patience. Give
me a couple of hours, give me a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   As he headed for a vacation at his beachfront home in South
Carolina, Williams promised a decision no later than July 7, the
day before the summer recruiting period begins. He added that there
could be ''a definite plan'' in the next 24 to 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   A native of North Carolina and a 10-year Smith assistant,
Williams said he has had 23 firm offers from NBA and major college
programs since taking the Kansas job in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ''With only one exception, every one of those situations have
been handled with one phone call,'' he said. ''I have shown my love
and loyalty for Kansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Few coaches in any sport enjoy such love and loyalty from fans.
During Williams' tenure, he has made a tradition of buying
doughnuts every morning before home games and passing them out to
students who camped out all night for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked out of Allen Fieldhouse following the news
conference, about 200 people, mostly students, greeted him with
cheers and applause and banners urging him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   One large banner read, ''Please don't go.'' Another said, ''We
love you Roy.''
</P>
<P>
   As he waded into the crowd signing autographs and shaking hands,
a little girl handed him a rose. Taking it from her hand, he picked
up the child and hugged her, wiping tears from his eyes as the
people cheered.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes earlier, Williams said all he had agreed to do was
to talk about the job with North Carolina officials. He denied any
formal offer had even been made.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's not a lot else I can tell you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas athletic director Bob Frederick, who came under heat for
hiring an obscure assistant coach 12 years ago, sat at the table
next to Williams and sounded optimistic about keeping him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on the conversations we had this morning, I think we
have a good chance of keeping coach Williams,'' Frederick said. ''I
know he's really struggling with this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   A protege of Smith, Williams admitted it would be difficult to
tell his old boss no.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it would be harder telling my players no,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One player, senior forward Kenny Gregory, said earlier that he
had dismissed reports Williams had decided to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it was a done deal, coach would have enough respect to talk
to the players first. He always said he would,'' Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Chancellor Robert Hemenway said the school was privileged
to have Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our hope and fervent desire is that the best basketball coach
in America will continue to practice his craft at KU,'' he said
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' North Carolina ties have remained strong. Both his son
and daughter went to school there. His wife is from North Carolina
and her family is still there.
</P>
<P>
   ''My family is not 100 percent on what direction I should go,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who turns 50 on Aug. 1, is 329-82 in 12 seasons at
Kansas since leaving Smith's Tar Heel staff. He took the Jayhawks
to the Final Four in 1991 and 1993 and led Kansas to a 286-60
record in the '90s, the best of any NCAA Division I school. Before
him, no college coach had reached 300 victories before 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the past nine years, Williams' teams have claimed seven
conference championships.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a day I hoped would never come,'' Williams said. ''I'm
very happy here.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Roy Williams:
www.jayhawks.org/mensbasketball/coaches/mbbwilliams.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
