<HEADLINE> White Sox 10, Red Sox 4  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Frank Thomas and Brook Fordyce each hit two home
runs Friday night as the Chicago White Sox powered past the Boston
Red Sox 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas hit a solo homer in the fifth inning off Bryce Florie and
added another solo drive, his 22nd, an inning later off Rheal
Cormier.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas now has 12 homers in June, tying his personal best for
one month. He also has three multi-homer games in the last nine
days.
</P>
<P>
   Fordyce hit a solo shot in the fifth and a two-run shot in the
eighth, giving him three for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Lee also homered for Chicago, which improved its lead
over Cleveland in the AL Central to 9&AMP;frac12; games.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Parque (8-2) won his fifth straight decision in span of
seven starts, allowing eight hits and three runs -- one earned -- in
5 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, its lineup and rotation ravaged by injuries, including
one to ace Pedro Martinez, got homers from rookie Izzy Alcantara
and Scott Hatteberg. The Red Sox lost for the eighth time in 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   Hipolito Pichardo (2-1), who missed the entire 1999 season after
having reconstructive surgery on his right elbow, made his first
start since Aug. 20, 1998, when he was with Kansas City, and lasted
only four innings. He gave up six hits and four runs.
</P>
<P>
   Fordyce's single, a double by Jose Valentin and an intentional
walk to Thomas loaded the bases in the third. Magglio Ordonez drove
in a run with a grounder before Chris Singleton hit a two-run
double into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez left the game in the top of the sixth after pulling up
lame while running on a double in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Fordyce's second homer made it 4-0 in the bottom of the fourth,
before Boston broke through for three against Parque in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Alcantara led off with his first major league home and, after
Parque retired the next two hitters, Valentin misplayed Jason
Varitek's grounder for an error. Nomar Garciaparra singled and Carl
Everett was hit by a pitch to load the bases before Morgan Burkhart
delivered a two-run single to make it 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' homer off Florie, a liner just over the left-field
fence, gave the White Sox a 5-3 lead in the fifth. After Ordonez
doubled and moved to third on an infield out, Lee hit his 15th
homer to finish Florie after one-third of an inning.
Notes: The error was Valentin's 18th of the season. ... The Red
Sox have allowed a homer in 15 straight games, a club record. ...
Thomas also hit 12 homers in May 1994. He now has 18 career
multi-homer games. ... The five homers tied a season high for the
White Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
