<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ark. Court Sues To Disbar Clinton
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton was sued Friday by an Arkansas
Supreme Court committee seeking to strip him of his law license. The committee's
lawsuit accused the president of engaging in serious misconduct in the Monica
Lewinsky affair, including false testimony, that ''damages the legal
profession.'' The five-page lawsuit asks that Clinton be disbarred for
conducting ''himself in a manner that violates the model rules of professional
conduct as adopted by the Arkansas Supreme Court.'' The president has 30 days to
respond, and his private attorney vowed a vigorous fight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
100 Countries Approve War Tribunal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Two documents were approved by more than 100 countries
for the world's first permanent war crimes tribunal Friday -- a move the United
States said was a step toward exempting Americans from prosecution by the court.
But with the United States clearly in mind, many countries warned that they will
oppose any changes to the 1998 Rome treaty creating the International Criminal
Court -- and any interpretation of its rules that makes a dispensation for one
country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
8 Dead in Denmark Pearl Jam Concert
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- At least eight people were crushed to death and
three others were injured Friday when fans rushed the stage during a Pearl Jam
concert at one of Europe's largest rock festivals. Members of Pearl Jam had
urged the crowd to move back because people were being pressed up against the
stage, and the warning was repeated on loudspeakers, Danish radio said. The band
halted its performance and the following session by The Cure was canceled. But
concerts on six other stages went on, a festival spokesman said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Perot Shuns Bid for President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Two-time presidential candidate Ross Perot Friday turned down
backer' efforts to put his name on the Reform Party's primary ballot, removing a
potential hurdle for Pat Buchanan's bid. The Texas billionaire decided against
running in the primary because he had no intention of actually competing for the
White House in November, Russell Verney, Perot's spokesman, said. Verney said
Perot didn't want to put his name on the Reform ballot only to stop Buchanan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Can't Find E-Mails
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House has yet to recover any missing e-mails
sought by investigators, a judge disclosed Friday, but it is turning over backup
tapes that might contain the messages to Independent Counsel Robert Ray and the
Justice Department. Two law enforcement officials told The Associated Press that
the FBI will now step in and try to retrieve the missing e-mails. Congress, Ray
and Justice are investigating whether the e-mail problem was an innocent
mistake, as the White House contends, or part of an effort to obstruct their
investigations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Arrest Expelled Senator
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Police arrested former senator Luiz Estevao on
Friday, two days after he was expelled for misconduct and lost his congressional
immunity from prosecution. Estevao faces more than a dozen charges of financial
wrongdoing, including the embezzlement of nearly $93 million earmarked for the
construction of the yet-unfinished Sao Paulo State Labor Courthouse by his
construction firm.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't To Limit UC Role at Los Alamos
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a string of security lapses, the Energy Department
gave notice Friday that it intends to strip the University of California of its
security and some management responsibilities involving nuclear weapons programs
at Los Alamos and another government research lab. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson told the university its contracts for managing the Los Alamos and
Lawrence Livermore labs ''must be restructured ... to make much-needed
improvements to security.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 50; Nasdaq Climbs 89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rallying in the final hour of trading, the Dow Jones
industrial average Friday erased a small loss and finished up 49.85 at 10,447.89
in heavy trading. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by a narrow margin. The Nasdaq
composite index, lifted by computer chips and semiconducter stocks, rose 88.88
to 3,966.11.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White Sox Defeat Red Sox 10-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Frank Thomas and Brook Fordyce each hit two home runs Friday
night as the Chicago White Sox powered past the Boston Red Sox 10-4. Thomas hit
a solo homer in the fifth inning off Bryce Florie and added another solo drive,
his 22nd, an inning later off Rheal Cormier. Thomas now has 12 homers in June,
tying his personal best for one month. He also has three multi-homer games in
the last nine days. Fordyce hit a solo shot in the fifth and a two-run shot in
the eighth, giving him three for the season.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
